<HEADLINE> Britain to Consider Reducing Forces in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain will consider reducing
its military presence in the Gulf region if Iraq fully comply with
the agreement signed with the United Nations on arms inspections,
a senior British defense official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There will be some considerations that the size of our
military presence in the region should be reduced if Iraq
completely implements the agreement," British Secretary of State
for Defense George Robertson told reporters at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, who arrived here Sunday night on a two-day official
visit, said Britain "was satisfied with Baghdad's allowance for
U.N. arms inspectors access to sites suspected of containing
weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
But he pointed the implementation of the U.N.-Iraq agreement
"still has to be tested."
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. signed the agreement in late February, under
which Baghdad agreed to unconditionally and completely allow U.N.
arms inspectors, charged with dismantling weapons of mass
destruction in Iraq, to enter any sites.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States remained cautious about that and
kept their troops on alert to monitor Iraq's implementation of the
accord.
</P>
<P>
London deployed in the Gulf waters two aircraft carriers and
some other warships as part of the military buildup for an
possible use of force against Iraq in a four-month-long standoff
over weapons inspection. Washington has three aircraft carrier
battling groups in the area.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Robertson stressed that he "very much hope that
the Iraqi people's plight will be eased by the U.K.-co-sponsored
resolution which doubled the oil-for-food program."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved last month to allow Baghdad
to sell 5.3-billion-U.S.-dollar-worth of oil in six-month period
to buy food and medicine needed in Iraq. The figure more than
doubled the 2 billion dollars of oil sales under the oil-for-food
deal struck between Baghdad and the U.N. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Robertson has held talks with senior
officials of the United Arab Emirates and discussed with them
bilateral relations and the latest developments in the Gulf
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
