<HEADLINE> Sudan to Return Expropriated Egyptian Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese relevant ministries
have started carrying out President Omar Al-Bashir's decision to
return expropriated Egyptian property, Sudanese media reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Higher Education and Scientific Research Ibrahim
Ahmed Omar announced that his ministry has started to consider
return the Egyptians the educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
According to sources of the Sudanese embassy in Cairo,
Al-Bashir's instructions cover the expropriated Egyptian property
including the branch of Cairo University in Khartoum, public
schools and the guest house of an Egyptian irrigation and
hydrological survey team.
</P>
<P>
These properties have been seized by Khartoum over chilling
relations after an Islamist-backed government assumed power in
Sudan in 1989.
</P>
<P>
In a step towards improving the long-hit ties with Egypt,
Al-Bashir has ordered necessary arrangements to restore Egyptian
property in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Omar said that his ministry has prepared some relevant materials
and will convey them to the Egyptian side for an agreement on
returning these institutions.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Irrigation Ministry has also started to study the
president's decision to consider returning the guest house to the
Egyptians, which was confiscated by the Sudanese government in
1994.
</P>
<P>
However, the student union of the Nilain University, formerly
the branch of Cairo University in Khartoum, Sunday issued a
statement in which it declared its refusal of the decision to
return the university to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir's decision came just a month after the two countries
resumed the river Nile navigation after a hiatus of three years, a
move hailed by both sides as a good turn after a long period of
strained ties.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors were at odds over a border dispute and have
traded accusations of harboring militants and oppositions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
