<HEADLINE> White House Spokeswoman Questions Clinton Accuser's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A White House spokeswoman
Monday questioned the credibility of U.S. President Bill Clinton's
latest accuser, saying former White House volunteer Kathleen
Willey's account of an alleged sexual advance is "contradicted" by
her positive attitude toward Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Appearing on morning television talk shows, White House
spokeswoman Ann Lewis said Mrs. Willey's description on CBS' "60
Minutes" Sunday of the 1993 Oval Office encounter with Clinton
"surprised" her.
</P>
<P>
"What I saw last night was someone who talked about being
angry, feeling that she has been taken advantage of. And yet in
1996, when she was no longer associated with the president or the
White House, she came to see me and said `I really want to work in
this campaign,'" said Lewis on NBC's "Today" show.
</P>
<P>
"There was such a contradiction between what I saw and heard
last night and the person I met with in 1996," Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
Lewis denied that she was trying to spread a White House
"message" to rebut Mrs. Willey's account, saying this is her
"personal message."
</P>
<P>
Willey said the story she was telling on television was the
same one she swore to before a Whitewater grand jury last week.
Clinton has given a sworn deposition denying her account.
</P>
<P>
Willey's family finances were in a state of collapse and she
wanted a paying White House job when she came to see Clinton on
November 29, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "has no idea why she said what she did or whether she
now believes that's what happened," said a White House statement
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's lawyer, Robert Bennett, said on ABC's "This Week"
that "there is substantial material of what she has said which is
under seal, which has not been released, which seriously
undercuts" her story.
</P>
<P>
"I think in fairness it's important... to note that there have
been at least five versions of this encounter," former White House
counsel Jack Quinn said on CBS' "Face the Nation."
</P>
<P>
The president said earlier he may have kissed Mrs. Willey on
the forehead to comfort her but that there was nothing sexual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
