<HEADLINE> SAARC Members Urged to Sign Investment Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior official from the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) has
called upon the member states to sign an agreement for protecting
investment in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar held on Monday in Karachi, Kanti Kumar
Podar, president of SAARC Chamber of Commerce and Industry (SCCI),
said SCCI is looking forward to a regional agreement for
investment promotion and protection among South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Podar said such an agreement would encourage export-oriented
joint ventures in the SAARC region and facilitate their financing
from non-SAARC regions.
</P>
<P>
He also called for formulating a time-bound action plan for the
transition from South Asian Preferential Trading Agreement (SAPTA)
to South Asian Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, entitled "SAARC Economic Union by 2008", was
jointly organized by SCCI and the Federation of Pakistan Chambers
of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Podar said that the Customs Union of SAARC is to be achieved by
2005 through adopting a common external tariff and allowing free
flow of capital.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the delay in the third round negotiations under
SAPTA, he said this round should have been completed by the end of
1997.
</P>
<P>
Podar hoped that commerce ministers of the seven SAARC member
countries would complete the negotiations in Islamabad next month.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the SAARC states are currently constrained by
lack of infrastructure and communication linkages between them.
</P>
<P>
He called for the immediate signing of an agreement to
facilitate the movement of goods and people by road.
</P>
<P>
"Similar regional agreements at SAARC level for promotion of
shipping, railways and airlines are necessary to further the cause
of free trade," Podar added.
</P>
<P>
SAARC comprises Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
