<HEADLINE> Foreign Currency Market Stable in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, (Xinhua) March 17 -- The foreign currency market in
Romania is following a positive trend, the daily Curentul said in
Tuesday's issue.
</P>
<P>
The daily quotes Adrian Vasilescu, the communication director
of Romania's Central Bank (BNR), as saying that "BNR stopped
intervening in the interbank foreign currency market three weeks
ago."
</P>
<P>
Vasilescu is also quoted as saying that an increased foreign
currencies demand was recorded at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The bank-to-costumer and the bank-to-bank operations in the
first three months of 1998 were equal on total transactions, which
proves that the Romanian market is functional and becoming more
active, Vasilescu said.
</P>
<P>
According to specialists at BNR, the Bank's main objective is
to control the money supply and inflation, with ulterior control
of interest rates and exchange rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
