<HEADLINE> EU Suspends Preferential Import Tariffs for Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural ministers from 15
European Union (EU) countries decided to remove preferential
tariffs on the import of pork, poultry and fruit juice from the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's decision was a response to an import quota of 24,000
tons a year imposed by the Czech government on EU apples starting
in 1998, the EU said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures passed by Czech authorities, the EU will
have to pay a 95 percent duty for its above-quota apples exported
to the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
According to the European Commission, the EU's executive body,
the suspension of preferential tariffs will only serve as the
first step, said the statement. The adoption of further measures
will depend on how the dispute develops.
</P>
<P>
The new Czech quota would cause an estimated potential loss of
seven million ECU (some 7.5 million U.S. dollars) to the EU apple
growers, said EU sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
