<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British FM Visits Har Homa, Despite Israeli Anger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Despite Israel's anger and the
bitter weather, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook toured
Tuesday afternoon the controversial Har Homa in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival in Jerusalem from Gaza, where he met Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, Cook, accompanied by Israeli officials, went
ahead to the site.
</P>
<P>
Israel broke ground for the construction of a Jewish settlement
on Har Homa a year ago, leading to a standstill in the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
When Cook reached Har Homa, he was confronted with a group of
Israeli nationalist, rightwing demonstrators who chanted "Cook, go
home" in protest of his visit.
</P>
<P>
But about a dozen peace advocates of the Israeli Peace Now
movement greeted the British top diplomat to show their support
for his position on demanding Israel's halt of settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
Israel, displeased with Cook's trip to the site, canceled
police escort for Cook on his way to Har Homa, but deployed a
large contingent of policemen at the site in an effort to curb
radical protesters.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit was very brief not only because of his tight
schedule, but also because of the hail storm, which was associated
with strong wind and sporadic rain.
</P>
<P>
He was briefed by Israeli officials at the scene and talked
with local Palestinians to get their respective accounts of the
situation there.
</P>
<P>
Cook, as a representative of the European Union (EU), is on a
tour of the Middle East aimed at helping revive the peace
process. He has visited Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinian
self-rule areas, and will travel to Syria and Lebanon. Britain is
holding the rotating presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cook's insistence on seeing for himself Har Homa angered
Israel, which warned that the visit might undermine EU's role in
mediating the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strong opposition of the Jewish state, Cook dropped
his original plan to visit Har Homa with Palestinian Minister for
Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini and agreed to be escorted by
Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
Israel contended that it has sovereignty over the whole
Jerusalem, including the Arab east part it occupied in 1967.
</P>
<P>
By visiting Har Homa, Cook was trying to send a clear message
to Israel that the EU views its settlement activity as a major
obstacle to progress in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting Arafat in Gaza, Cook made it clear that
Israel must stop settlement expansion in order to advance the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Cook is to hold talks with Palestinian
officials in East Jerusalem, and with Israeli leaders, including
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
