<HEADLINE> Feature: China's Tibetan Art Exhibition Warmly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Phrases like "Very good", "Nice
exhibit, welcome again" and "Breath-taking" appeared repeatedly in
the two visitor books at the six-day China's Tibetan Art
Exhibition opened on Monday in Kathmandu, capital of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"I'm really pleased to see this grand art exhibition," a Nepali
visitor wrote in the book. "We enjoy very much seeing your
country's arts. Thanks for your exhibition, " another visitor
echoed.
</P>
<P>
Rabin Bajracharya, a student learning the Chinese language,
said that in the past he knew little about Tibet, but now he came
to know more about it through the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetan culture is unique, very similar to the Newari
culture, so it is easily acceptable for me," he said. Newari is
one of the minority nationalities in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
On display at the exhibition sponsored by the Chinese Embassy
in Nepal are about 100 pictures and some 500 objects relating to
archaeology, animal husbandry, agriculture, dress and personal
adornment, tangka and masks in Tibet known as "the Roof of the
World."
</P>
<P>
As most common traditional art products of Tibetan Buddhism,
tangka depicts a wide range of subjects including historical
events, biographies, religious doctrines, Tibetan natural
conditions and social customs, folklore and mythologies. Ever
since the exhibition opened, stream of visitors poured in
continuously, according to a cultural official from the Chinese
Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa noted in his
inaugural speech that relations between Nepal and China are
greatly consolidated by promoting at the people's level
understanding of each other's culture.
</P>
<P>
"I like it because Tibetan art and culture are beautiful," said
Nabin Subelli, a Nepalese businessman.
</P>
<P>
A teacher from Nepal's Tribhuvan University showed great
interest in the pictures about samples of cultural relics from the
New Stone Age unearthed in Tibet. "They are informative and nice,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Deepak Dahal, a social worker, said he was especially
interested in the exhibits concerning the Buddhist culture and
agriculture, because they are the same as Nepal's.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed here that the exhibition is bound to be
succeeded in achieving its aim of further strengthening the
cultural ties and understanding between Nepal and the Tibet
Autonomous Region of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
