<HEADLINE> Kabila Slams West for Rumor-Mongering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- President of Democratic Congo
Laurent Kabila Tuesday blamed the west for spreading rumors that
scandalize his government through the use of advanced information
technology.
</P>
<P>
Kabila arrived here Monday evening and held talks with
President Robert Mugabe which ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after their talks in Harare, Kabila said
his country was receiving a lot bad publicity through the use of
the internet.
</P>
<P>
He said when he marched from the eastern part and ousted the
late former Zaire leader Mobutu Sese Seko last year, he received
a lot of support from the west.
</P>
<P>
''We do not expect any more support from them now,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
Explaining one of the incidents, Kabila said 19 armed rebels
from Rwanda, Uganda and Burundi had been executed because they
were captured, questioned and found trying to cause civil unrest
in the country.
</P>
<P>
''It was right. It is in our interest that no one is allowed
to use our territory to launch war on our country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same press briefing, Mugabe said he was concerned about
the rumors and false information on the political situation in
the central African country.
</P>
<P>
''These rumors have to be dispelled, and we will support
Kabila to dispel rumors that all is not well and that there is
resistance to democracy by Kabila and his government,'' Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe disclosed that he was briefed on the difficulties faced
by Kabila's government as it tried to overcome deprivation, lack
of food, transport and other facilities in general.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also consulted on regional issues as both are
members of the Southern African Development Community and the
Organization of African Unity, especially on how to solve the
problems in the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and his delegation left Harare for Kinshasa Tuesday
afternoon after his two-day visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
