<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Revokes State of Emergency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Tuesday revoked the state of emergency imposed after the
October 28 foiled coup.
</P>
<P>
He announced here that the state of emergency has been lifted
because there has been no more threat to the national security of
the country since the coup suspects started appearing in court
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The president said the state can continue to bring the
suspects to court and ensure that their conduct is within the
requirements of the law.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, however, warned that he will not hesitate to invoke
the state of emergency again if there is any threat to the peace
of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency was imposed one day after the coup
attempt and extended for another three months on January 29 this
year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 95 people, including former President Kenneth
Kaunda, had been arrested after the coup.
</P>
<P>
Following international appeals for Kaunda's immediate release
or an early law process, the government transferred Kaunda to the
treatment of being under arrest house on December 31 of 1997,
just six days after his being placed into prison in alleged
involvement in the coup.
</P>
<P>
Last month Kaunda, who had been in power for 27 years after
Zambia's independence in 1964 till 1991 when he was defeated by
Chiluba in the multi-party elections, was formally charged with
misprison of treason.
</P>
<P>
He was alleged to have known between October 26 and 28 last
year that certain Zambian army officers intended to commit
treason but did not pass such information on to Chiluba or other
senior leaders of the country, or try to stop the coup.
</P>
<P>
In January, Kaunda was charged with conspiring with some army
officers and two top leaders of two other opposition parties to
topple the government.
</P>
<P>
Some donor countries have been calling for lifting the state
of emergency in Zambia and some even went so far as to withhold
their aid payments to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Buses to Use Gas to Replace Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China's first group of 120
environmentally friendly buses with liquefied petroleum gas (LPG)
will hit the road here in May in an effort to control the
deteriorating air pollution in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The city will also set up an LPG station for the buses.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a local automobile plant and Beijing LPG
Company have developed a new kind of LPG truck which can use
either gasoline or LPG. Some 34 such trucks are available on the
market.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 100 automobiles in Beijing have replaced
gasoline with LPG and three LPG stations have been set up.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has been suffering from abundant emissions from its 1.3
million automobiles, said an environmental expert, and "the use of
LPG will produce much less pollution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
