<HEADLINE> French Right Wing Opposition Rejects FN Alliance Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- France's Rally for the Republic
(RPR) and Union for French Democracy (UDF) said Tuesday that they
will not seek alliance with the far-right National Front (FN).
</P>
<P>
The RPR and UDF, two main right-wing opposition parties,
rejected categorically the proposal by the FN to set up an
alliance, though they suffered a major setback in the regional
elections Sunday by losing nearly half the 20 regional councils or
parliaments they controlled to the left-wing coalition.
</P>
<P>
The FN won 15 plus percent of votes and will play an arbitrary
role in electing the president of eight regional councils or
parliaments, where the right wing and Socialist-led left wing are
running shoulder to shoulder.
</P>
<P>
In a ``formal instruction'' to all its elected regional
deputies, the RPR asked them to ``refuse to take whatever part''
in allying with the FN.
</P>
<P>
The UDF said there would be ``neither alliance, nor compromise,
nor agreement with the National Front for the election of the
presidents of the region.''
</P>
<P>
The FN President Jean-Marie Le Pen proposed Monday that FN
support RPR and UDF in exchange for a six-point program on
economic and social policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
