<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Launches Road Safety Bid over Easter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa launched a
road safety campaign Tuesday to curb road deaths over the Easter
weekend, South Africa Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Launching the second phase of the Arrive Alive campaign in
Pretoria, Transport Minister Mac Maharaj said the 10-million-Rand
(2 million U.S. Dollars) program would run until the end of
April.
</P>
<P>
The campaign would especially highlight the dangers of
speeding and driver fatigue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from previous years have shown that speeding is a
particularly serious problem over the short Easter holidays, when
South Africans seem to rush to get to their destinations.
</P>
<P>
Maharaj said the success of the first phase of the Arrive
Alive campaign, from last October to January, surpassed all
expectations when it reduced the road death toll over this period
by almost a third, from the previous year's 3,170 to 2,139 this
year.
</P>
<P>
Half of the budget for the campaign would be spent on
communication, including radio and television commercials
emphasizing the dangers of speeding, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
