<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Stress Importance of Cultural &AMP; Ethical Progress (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- While showing great concern about
economic growth, laid-off workers, public security and the rule of
law, lawmakers attending the ongoing session of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, have not forgot
to underline the importance of cultural and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
In their panel discussions on a government work report
submitted to the session for examination and approval, the
lawmakers have reached consensus that unremitting efforts must be
made to promote China's cultural and ethical progress, which is
indispensable for all-round social progresses.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades of reforms and opening-up, China has
maintained an annual average growth rate of about 10 percent for
its national economy, which has resulted in a far better material
life for its people.
</P>
<P>
The government work report notes: "In developing a market
economy and opening to the outside world, we are confronted with a
new situation and new tasks in promoting socialist cultural and
ethical progress. In concentrating on promoting economic
development, we are prone to neglect the promotion of cultural and
ethical progress."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Lu Shanzhen, who is president of the Beijing Teachers'
University, said that promotion of cultural and ethical progress
is becoming ever more important as the economy grows steadily.
</P>
<P>
"What's the point of economic growth if all people are
spiritually decadent and unwilling to serve their motherland?" he
asked.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers agreed that in the past five years, the Chinese
government has made remarkable achievements in promoting cultural
and ethical progress, whose significance has also been realized by
more and more people.
</P>
<P>
They noted that in many Chinese cities today, young volunteers
are actively engaged in community service, some taxi drivers offer
free ride to senior citizens, and local libraries are often packed
on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lei Feng, a famous model of altruism in the 1960s,
has once again become one of the most admired heroes in the
Chinese people's hearts, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Stress Importance of Cultural &AMP; Ethical Progress (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Li Bo from the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, who is
an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said that
science, technology, culture and education, which are regarded as
part of cultural and ethical progress in China, could provide the
most powerful intellectual backing for material progress.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that promotion of cultural and ethical progress will
add great impetus to economic growth in comparatively
underdeveloped regions in central and western China," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Xiang Jianping from east China's Zhejiang Province cited
the example of Wenzhou, a booming coastal city in Zhejiang noted
for its highly developed private economy, to explain the
importance of cultural and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
She said that in the primary stage of development, Wenzhou
people used to neglect cultural and ethical progress, and that
with an atmosphere of money worship prevailing in the city, fake
and shoddy commodities proliferated and almost destroyed the
fledgling local economy.
</P>
<P>
"In recent years, people in Wenzhou have drawn lessons from the
past and made a lot of efforts to promote local cultural and
ethical progress, which has helped the city to improve its image
across the country and usher in greater prosperity," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Fu Yiming, another lawmaker from Zhejiang, suggested the
society make great efforts to curb the spread of evils like
pornography, gambling and drugs and prevent the rise of juvenile
delinquency.
</P>
<P>
Some other deputies noted that the promotion of cultural and
ethical progress would teach people how to correctly handle the
relationship between personal and collective, partial and overall,
and immediate and long-term interests, and thus help ease social
tensions caused by layoffs of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Deputy He Shaochuan from east China's Fujian Province pointed
out that cultural and ethical progress relies heavily on the
improvement of the quality of all people, especially of leading
officials, and greater efforts for relevant legislation.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Xu Zhiqin from southwest China's Chongqing City
suggested more revolutionary relics be used in the promotion of
cultural and ethical progress to influence people with the spirit
of revolutionary martyrs.
</P>
<P>
"It is also necessary to encourage writers and artists to
create more works of high taste that can appeal to both the more
and the less cultured," said Qin Bailan, a deputy from northeast
China's Liaoning Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SBP Lifts Controls on U.S. Dollar Transactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The State Bank of Pakistan
(SBP) has lifted controls over U.S. dollar transactions by
allowing dealers to fix their own rates.
</P>
<P>
The bank made the announcement Tuesday with effect from March
24, permitting authorized dealers to quote different exchange
rates for the U.S. dollar like other currencies.
</P>
<P>
The bank also decided to widen its buy and sell spread for the
green back from 0.5 percent to 1 percent and allow banks to quote
their own dollar-rupee exchange rates for transactions.
</P>
<P>
The bank on January 20 allowed authorized dealers to set their
own exchanges rates for about 24 foreign currencies other than the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, importers will be free to purchase U.S.
dollars for imports, in ready or forward, from any authorized
dealer like other foreign currencies subject to the procedure and
stipulations of the SBP announcement.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the same rules will apply for the sale of U.S.
dollars as is the case with the sale of other foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
SBP also said it will discontinue publication of spot rates for
the U.S. dollar for the public and that of the U.S. dollar bill
buying rate by the Foreign Exchange Rates Committee from March 24.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
