<HEADLINE> Qaidam Basin China's Vital Resource Base in Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Along with the central
government's strategy to develop China's central and western
areas, the Qaidam Basin on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau is expected
to be a major base of natural resources in the next century.
</P>
<P>
According to a plan worked out by southwestern Qinghai Province
where the basin is situated, reserves of the dotted saline lakes,
such as petroleum, natural gas and other minerals, will be tapped
in the next 15 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The 250,000 sq km basin, one of the three biggest basins in
China, has scores of proven minerals, which have an estimated
potential value of 20 trillion yuan (2.4 trillion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The basin has 33 saline lakes, and their salt deposits with
contents of potassium, magnesium and lithium, make up more than 90
percent of the related deposits in the country, according to Ma
Peihua, deputy director of the Qinghai Institute of Saline Lakes
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Approximately one-third of China's arable land suffers a
shortage of potassium, so the production of potassium chloride
will be key projects in developing the saline lakes, said Ma, who
is here attending the annual session of China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Production of potassium fertilizers in the Qairhan Saline Lake
only reaches 350,000 tons each year.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the operation of a Sino-Israel joint
venture with a yearly output of 800,000 tons of potassium
chloride, the Qaidam Basis will turn out 1.3 million tons of
potassium chloride and 150,000 tons of potassium sulphate annually
by the year 2000. In this sense, Qaidam will be the country's
largest production base of saline chemicals.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, other types of minerals will be exploited, Ma
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
According to Jiang Jiemin, director of the Qinghai Petroleum
Administration, the central government has decided to focus on
the exploitation of natural gas resources in the Qaidam Basin.
</P>
<P>
The crude oil and natural gas reserves are estimated at 4.06
billion tons and 1.05 trillion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the production of crude oil was 1.6 million tons, and
production of natural gas 200 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jiemin further estimated that by the year 2005, Qaidam
will turn out five million tons of crude oil and five billion
cubic meters of natural gas, which will make up one-thirtieth of
China's total oil and gas production.
</P>
<P>
At the turn of the century, large projects to make polyvinyl
chloride, caustic soda, synthetic ammonia and carbamide will be
set up.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the basin boasts huge reserves of nonferrous and
nonmetal minerals, with the deposits of asbestos accounting for 60
percent of the country's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
