<HEADLINE> Southern African Expecting Regional Tourist Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A single regional visa for
South Africa, Swaziland and Mozambique may be introduced to
encourage cross-border tourism and tourism-generated investment,
South African Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
The visa would be treated separately from a proposed South
African Development Community (SADC) protocol on the movement of
its member citizens, Jordan said Monday at a ministerial meeting
in Mbabane, capital of Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said tourism policy makers had been discussing how to do
away with the visas of the three countries needed to visit South
Africa's KwaZulu-Natal province, Swaziland and southern
Mozambique, as the three bordering regions are rich in tourist
attractions.
</P>
<P>
The largely unspoiled area in the region is to be developed,
Jordan said at the meeting, aimed at discussing the
600-million-Rand (121-million-U.S. Dollars) Lubombo development
project.
</P>
<P>
"We need a common approach to soften our borders in specific
areas... so that we can sell them both to investors and to
tourists as a package," Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the tourist visa would only allow for free
access to certain projects across borders in the region, but not
the free movement in SADC member states as the proposed SADC
protocol would do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
