<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Institutional Restructuring Vital Step in Political Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- "The success of institutional
restructuring will facilitate extending the space of political
structural reform and improving socialist democracy and legality,"
Xing Bensi, vice-president of the Party School of the Communist
Party of China's (CPC) Central Committee, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wang Jiaqiu, another vice-president of the Party
School, said: "Taking institutional restructuring as a point of
breakthrough in reforming political set-up not only complies with
popular feelings but creates a good social environment for relevant
political reform in other aspects, and this shows the political
wisdom of Chinese leaders."
</P>
<P>
According to Dong Fureng, a noted economist and a member of the
CPPCC National Committee, when economic basis undergoes changes,
the superstructure, including the way of how political power is
operated, should be adapted to such changes, and political
restructuring reforms, including those concerning government
institutions and their functions, are imperative.
</P>
<P>
With the Plan Concerning Institutional Restructuring of the
State Council approved by the ongoing session of top legislature
with overwhelming votes, a vital step has taken in this regard,
and some Chinese theoretical authorities reached consensus that
the current reform will crack the hard nut for China's overall
political restructuring.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua this morning, Xing explained that
the fundamental goal of political reform in China is to build a
democratic socialist country ruled by law.
</P>
<P>
"The arrow is ready to be released now that it has been put on
the bow," said Xing, who is concurrently the editor-in-chief of
Qiushi (seeking truth), a theoretical periodical of the CPC
Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Without the restructuring, overstaffed government institutions
are hindrance to China's economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some new concepts reflected in the reform will be turned into
the new reality in the Party and state leadership system, Xing
said, and it will represent another important reform in the system
of the Party leadership and state power as well as another
breakthrough after the the life-long tenure of leading officials
was abrogated in 1982, Xing said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, it demonstrates the resolve of the central
government since it set forth such an unprecedented and detailed
institutional structural blueprint only six months after the 15th
CPC National Congress was convened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
