<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are the business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Shipping through the Suez Canal resumed Monday after a
delay of 10 hours because of high waves in both Port Said and
Suez and low visibility along the canal on account of a sandstorm
that swept Egypt for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's tourism revenues in 1997 amounted to 70
million U.S. dollars, an increase of 29 million dollars
compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Vice Chairman of Yemen's Tourism Authority Mohammed Qafla has
said that in 1997, Yemen received some 80,000 foreign tourists,
most of them were Europeans, especially from Italy, Germany and
France.
</P>
<P>
He said that 100,000 foreign tourists are expected to visit
Yemen in 1998.
</P>
<P>
SANAA: According to sources in the Yemeni oil industry,
Yemen's oil output is expected to rise to 500,000 barrels per day
by the year 2005, compared with a production level of 410,000
bpd expected to be achieved by Yemen this year.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Yemen's oil output will rise from 440,000
barrels per day in 1999 to 450,000 bpd in the year 2000, and that
it will further rise to 470,000 bpd in the year 2002. Yemen's oil
output at present amounts to 385,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's gross domestic product (GDP) for 1997
rose 1.9 percent compared with the around 4 percent in 1996,
according to figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics
(CBS) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure suggests that the recession of the Israel's economy
is deepening.
</P>
<P>
For the second half of 1997, there was a shrinking in
investments and a significant slowdown in activities in the
industrial and building sectors in Israel.
</P>
<P>
CBS said that the per capita GDP fell 0.5 percent in 1997 after
rising 1.8 percent in 1996 and 4.2 percent in 1995. The per capita
GDP for 1997 stood at 16,571 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
