<HEADLINE> China to Enact Law on Reporting Private Properties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China is to enact a new law
requiring government functionaries to report their private
properties to the government, according to Hu Kangsheng,
vice-chairman of the Subcommittee on Legislative Affairs of the
National People's Congress Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
This is intended to prevent government functionaries from
seeking personal gains by abusing their power and taking bribes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Pending legislation on personal property reporting has touched
a responsive chord among Chinese lawmakers, who are here attending
an annual NPC session.
</P>
<P>
"In our struggle for a clean government, self-restraint on the
part of government functionaries is necessary, but there must also
be restraint from the outside, a law in this regard," said deputy
Feng Xichu, mayor of Xi'an City.
</P>
<P>
"Education on ethics and disciplinary measures alone are not
enough to curb corruption. We must crack down on corruption by
law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The reporting of personal properties and incomes by government
functionaries is not only an important democratic system but also
a key anti-corruption measure, commented other deputies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Institutional Restructuring Vital Step in Political Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Jiaqiu acknowledged that "there are many difficulties
involved in the process of institutional restructuring, but
methods of coping with them can precisely enrich the contents of
China's political system." However, she said, in order to avoid
"the vacancy of functions", efforts will be intensified to foster
intermediary organizations and law-enforcement and supervision
departments while the government is in the process of shifting its
functions.
</P>
<P>
"Downsizing government institutions helps stop corruption,
whereas improving the system concerning civil servants is a major
guarantee for building a clean and honest government," she said.
</P>
<P>
Institutional reform is really the "most hard nut to crack" in
carrying out the country's in-depth political restructuring, she
once said, because it involves not only the redistribution of
power and interests but change of concepts in the people's mind,
ways of management method and the style of work."
</P>
<P>
The blueprint for institutional restructuring has "broken the
ice" and "opens navigation course" for overall political reform,
and then China's political reform will charge ahead like the "flow
of a turbulent river in spring time," Xing Bensi said.
</P>
<P>
As deputies to the ongoing the First Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), both Xing Bensi and Wang Jiaqiu
have outlined the future trends in China's political
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Xing held that the most crucial step in the next phase of
political restructuring is to improve democracy and legal system
and accomplish the administration of the state by law, and that
prime measures will precisely be adopted to enhance the
legislative and supervisory functions of the people's congresses,
and increase relations of mutual restrictions, which somewhat
resemble "checks and balance", among government organs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he added, the system of multi-party cooperation and
political consultations under the Communist Party leadership shall
be strengthened, so that the will of the state can incorporate the
aspirations of the people on a still more extensive scale.
</P>
<P>
"In promoting the process of political restructuring, China
will draw on some good experience of Western democracy instead of
copying it blindly," this theorist of great attainments said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Wang Jiaqiu acknowledged that the great set-up of
China's political system will remain unchanged. That is to say,
the entire system and framework will not be dismantled in the
course of the country's political institutional restructuring, but
the relevant restructuring will be advanced steadily and smoothly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
