<HEADLINE> Indonesia Pledges to Continue Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia Tuesday pledged to
continue its economic reforms, with or without the assistance fromaid he and oth
er officials will meet with an IMF
team here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Indonesia is ready to accept assistance from the IMF
and other countries but he regretted that a lot of
misunderstanding often occur.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia agreed in November last year to embrace an IMF reform
program in return for a 43-billion-U.S.-dollar aid package to
rescue its economy, crippled by the rapid decline of the rupiah
(national currency) against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF delayed its second tranche of assistance worth
3 billion dollars to Indonesia early this month because of the
"lack of reforms" in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since early February, the Indonesian government has repeatedly
said that it was preparing to set up a currency board, which would
peg the rupiah to a hard currency.
</P>
<P>
The IMF and other international monetary institutions opposed
the plan.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said the government is still in the stage of studying
the possibility of adopting a currency board to stabilize the
battered rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a better (solution to stabilize the rupiah), we
would do it," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Soeharto also instructed the ministers to
ensure enough food supplies and clothing, shelters and health
services for the people, Ginandjar said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
