<HEADLINE> Ningxia Makes Marked Progress in Education for Hui Girls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 94 percent of school-age
girls of Hui nationality in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
northwest China, attend schools, a local women's federation
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia, home to 1.7 million Hui people, has 600,000 girls of
Hui nationality, many of whom were unable to attend schools owing
to poverty and the trammel of old ideas, said Zhang Xiaosu,
chairwoman of the regional women's federation, who is here
attending the ongoing annual session of the National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the regional government has spent 3
million yuan building 300 primary schools in the mountainous
southern Ningxia, she said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the regional government spends 500,000 yuan each
year as a special fund to help girls with financial difficulties
attend schools.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, several anti-illiteracy campaigns have
been launched on a regional scale, enabling 400,000 illiterates in
the region to learn to read and write, she said.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia still has an arduous task in providing education for
all owing to its weak economic foundation. In poverty-stricken
southern Ningxia, she said, 13,000 girls still fail to attend
schools, of whom 70 percent are of Hui nationality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
