<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Reduce Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines Tuesday announced that the prime lending rates of
banks will be lowered early next week to a range of between 18.5
to 23.5 percent from the usual average of 24.17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said in a statement that
the imposition of the newly-adjusted lending rates is in
consonance with the improving 91-day T-bill rates which already
went down to 16.39 percent as of March 16.
</P>
<P>
Singson, however, explained that the minimum lending rates will
only be made available by banks to the super prime borrowers whose
credit standings are considered good.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank is still planning to bring down the
91-day T-bill rates by as much as 1 percent in a few weeks' time,
based on its consultation with the Bankers Association of the
Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
