<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Lu Confirms Her Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion and twice
Olympic bronze medalist Chen Lu confirmed here on Tuesday that
she has quit figure skating and will go to the United States for
study.
</P>
<P>
Chen, 21, who just returned from Nagano Olympic Games with a
bronze medal, said it was too old for a skater at her age.
</P>
<P>
"At 21, I think I have had no potential," said Chen, who won
the gold medal in the 1995 World Figure Skating Championships and
the silver the next year.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who began her figure skating career at four, said she
hoped to try best to offer a hand to the Chinese skaters whenever
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"Athough I have left the naitonal team, I will be a Chinese
for ever wherever I go," she said, "I hope I can give my
teammates some help in the future."
</P>
<P>
The former world Champion has been helping teammate Guo
Zhenxin polish his techniques these days before she leaves for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"She is a great skater. We'll miss her," said Guo, who
finished eighth in the men's individual event in the Nagano Games.
</P>
<P>
From world champion to the second-time Olympic bronze
medalist, Chen experienced dramatic ups and downs during the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who made history by winning China's first medal in
Lillehammar Olympic Games in 1994, slipped into a long time slump
after being dethroned by American Michelle Kwan in the 1996 World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997 figure skating Worlds in Lausanne, Chen was
eliminated from free skating as she placed a distance 25th in the
short program, failing to qualify for the Nagano Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"It's a shock," Chen said. "It's hard for me to accept the
reality."
</P>
<P>
She attributed the defeat to the foot injury that she
sustained in 1995. But it was an open secret that the seperation
with her long-time coach Li Mingzhu had affected her normal
training and form.
</P>
<P>
"The past is past. I only want to say I should thank her
(Li)," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
But Chen, who was expected to vanish from the circuit after
the defeat in Lausanne, finally stepped out of the shadow.
</P>
<P>
"Back from Lausanne, I determined that I would never retire
unless winning a medal in the Nagano Olympic Games or the
following World Championships," Chen recalled.
</P>
<P>
Then she began a Spardan training. She went on a diet but
trained much harder than ever.
</P>
<P>
The former world champion grasped the final chance last
October, qualifying for the Nagano Games by wining the Olympic
qualifying round in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
She went to Nagano on a low note, reiterating that there would
be no hope for her to win a medal.
</P>
<P>
When the Olympic bronze medal eventually draped around her
neck, she was too emotional to control herself with tears bathing
her cheeks on the podium.
</P>
<P>
"It was not merely a bronze medal," Chen said. "I think I set
an example for all the skaters. As long as you keep working
hard, you are sure to succeed."  
</P>
</TEXT>
