<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf States Sign Protocol on Controlling Marine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Kuwait-based
Regional Organization for Protection of Marine Environment
(ROPME) signed a protocol here Tuesday to control marine
transboundary movement and disposal of hazardous wastes.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that the
document titled "Tehran Protocol" was signed by representatives
from eight countries bordering the Persian Gulf and it would
be implemented after being approved by the respective
parliaments.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency gave no details about the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Vice President and Head of the Environment Protection
Organization Masoumeh Ebtekar told the ROPME meeting Tuesday that
the signing of the protocol was a significant development in line
with the environmental protection and security of the region.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation will pave the way for further security in
the region without the need of foreign intervention, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
The first Iranian female vice president said that as a
consequence of expanded industrial and urban activities, the
world's oceans have been increasingly polluted and the marine
ecosystems are continuously threatened by the exploitation of
natural resources such as oil.
</P>
<P>
Despite international efforts and conventions, the
transboundary movement of hazardous substances is a serious
concern at the global level, she said. And this trend is
particularly disturbing when developed countries deploy their
hazardous wastes to developing countries, she added.
</P>
<P>
The ROPME region is particularly susceptible to environmental
pollution, Ebtekar said, adding that the daily deployment of more
than 100 ships, numerous port facilities and oil refineries all
exert a negative effect on the marine ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
The ROPME comprises Iran, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman,
Iraq, Bahrain and the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
