<HEADLINE> 10,000 Textile Industry Spindles Destroyed in Qingdao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China's bloated textile industry
has undergone its second major cut this year, with 10,000 spindles
destroyed and melted today at Qingdao, a port city in East China's
Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 23, nearly 120,000 outdated spindles were melted in
Shanghai under the supervision by the China National Textile
Council (CNTC).
</P>
<P>
The destroyed spindles were manufactured 27 years ago. CNTC
officials attended the widely publicized event.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao plans to reduce 181,000 outdated spindles in two years,
laying off 10,000 textile workers.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao -- along with Shanghai, Tianjin, Wuhan, Jinan and
Dalian -- has been designated by CNTC to lead the country in
spindle reduction.
</P>
<P>
China plans to eliminate 10 million outdated spindles by the
end of the century, laying off 1.2 million workers. The target for
this year is to destroy 4.8 million spindles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
