<HEADLINE> China Sees Record Low Birth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The birth rate in China was 16.57
per 1,000 in 1997, 5.54 lower than that of 1989, said Peng Peiyun,
minister in charge of the State Commission of Family Planning
(SCFP) today.
</P>
<P>
The total population, including Hong Kong, was 1.243 billion at
the end of 1997, according to SCFP statistics.
</P>
<P>
During the last decade SCFP has been focusing its work on
residents in rural areas, especially those in remote and poor
areas, and trying to help them understand the need to reduce
family size, Peng told an ongoing national conference on family
planning, which opened in Beijing Sunday.
</P>
<P>
She said family planning departments at all levels have also
provided people with safer and more effective methods of
contraception and birth control.
</P>
<P>
SCFP has taken such measures as providing education and
services of reproductive health care nationwide and giving proper
sex education to youngsters to improve the health level of the
nation,
</P>
<P>
The country's investment in family planning has increased by
6.6 billion yuan (550,000 U.S. dollars) during the 1991-1995
period, up 127 percent than the 1986-1990 period, Peng said,
adding that SFPC has suggested to the central government doubling
the per capita family planning budget by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
