<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Daily Calls for Revision of Election Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate daily newspaper
Iran News Tuesday called for a revision of the country's election
laws to cancel the right of the Constitutional Guardians Council
(CGC) to disqualify any candidates.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Majlis by-elections held last Friday, the
daily said in its editorial that "it appears to have been far
wiser for the Guardians Council to have permitted the disqualified
candidates to compete for the Parliament."
</P>
<P>
"Ironically, the majority of rejected hopefuls had either been
deputies (Majlis members) before, or held sensitive posts after
the victory of the Revolution (in 1979) or in recent years," the
daily said, adding that CGC's rule was one of the main reasons for
the low turnout in the by-elections on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Many left-wing factions lodged strong protest against the
rejection of their hopefuls for the Majlis by-elections and
called on their followers not to participate in the polling.
</P>
<P>
"A statistic analysis of voters during the fifth Majlis shows
that on March 9, 1996, more than 2,444,000 voters turned out in
Tehran, whereas on March 13, 1998, only 273,000 voters cast their
ballots," the pro-leftwing newspaper noted.
</P>
<P>
The rejection of several left-wing candidates for the
by-elections triggered a violent factional clash in a rally in
front of Tehran University early this month, and put the right of
the Guardians Council to disqualify candidates under question.
</P>
<P>
Former Iranian Majlis Speaker Mehdi Karubi also openly
challenged the Constitutional Guardians Council (CGC) over its
right to disqualify candidates for the country's elections,
saying that the country's election laws did not authorize the
CGC to approve or reject the qualifications of any candidate but
only empowered it to generally supervise elections.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the left-wing factions demanded to
nullify the CGC's right to disqualify candidates in order to pave
the grounds for the success in the forthcoming elections for the
country's Experts Assembly later this year.
</P>
<P>
After the elections of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami last
May, the elections of the Experts Assembly would be sensitive for
both the left and right wings since the 83-member body has the
right to determine the fate of the country's supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said that the Iranian Majlis would discuss the
issue of revising election laws at the beginning of the new fiscal
year starting on March 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
