<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Confident China Pursuing Bolder Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- With progresses made in
step-by-step reforms in the last two decades, China is more
confident than ever in solving problems by continuing to carry out
reforms, and bolder ones at that.
</P>
<P>
Enhanced confidence is demonstrated at the on-going session of
the National people's Congress, China's parliament, when it
approved a reform program last week to restructure and downsize
the central government.
</P>
<P>
This confidence is a reflection of broad popular support for
continued reforms, including the government restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging there are still many tough problems to be
resolved, deputies to the NPC session believe that accelerating
reforms can help address the problems, which, in turn, is
conducive to maintaining economic growth and social stability.
</P>
<P>
The way the Chinese government has been dealing with the Asian
financial turmoil has convinced deputies that the central
leadership is competent and skillful in regulating the national
economy and coordinating relations between reform, development and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Lu Xueyi, a researcher with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, spoke highly of the central government's macro-economic
controls over recent years, which have successfully brought down
inflation while managing to achieve a high economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
"The achievements are impressive, " said Lu. "We have every
reason to trust such a leadership."
</P>
<P>
Deputies naturally expect much from the central authorities on
issues they are most concerned about: state enterprise reform,
reemployment of laid-off workers, risks in the banking sector,
corruption and public security.
</P>
<P>
To their relief, the central government generally is paying
adequate attention to all of the problems and taking corresponding
measures.
</P>
<P>
He Shulan, a construction worker from northeastern Heilongjiang
Province, said about half of the workers in her work unit have
left their work, but no one has ever tried to make trouble with
the factory management.
</P>
<P>
"They realize that a market economy means competition, which
will result in losers as well as winners," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They are trying to find jobs for themselves and some of them
have succeeded," He said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lu Xueyi of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences,
if workers' proper understanding of being laid off represents
grassroots support for economic reform, the move to restructure
and downsize the government should be seen as a reform move
initiated from upper above,
</P>
<P>
"The existing administrative structure has proved to be a
hindrance to economic reform," said Lu. "The government
restructuring is not only timely but also the only path the
country can take to deepen reforms."
</P>
<P>
As pointed out by a senior Chinese official,"Reform cannot
be free of risks or resistance, but it is the only way out and
there is no turning back." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
