<HEADLINE> Drought Ruins Namibian Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 70 percent of crops in
Namibia have been ruined due to the El Nino phenomenon and more
damage was expected if dry weather continues, a national farmers'
association said.
</P>
<P>
Namibian farmers would lose all their harvest this year if
there is no good rains within two weeks and the country's annual
yield could be decimated if it failed to rain at all, the
Agricultural Producer's Association said.
</P>
<P>
Officials said this year's drought, which has hit all farmers
from drought-resistant cotton, sorghum to mahangu growers, could
be compared with that in 1992, when the government was forced to
seek drought relief aid.
</P>
<P>
Mahangu crops in northern Namibia have started to wither and
farmers began to panic, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Grazing hit snags and water for animals was also running out
as some districts had not received rain since early March, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
