<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,100-year-old Lotus Soup A Clue to Earthquake Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A pot of lotus soup dating back
2,100 years has given scientists evidence that a southern Chinese
city has been relatively earthquake-free since then.
</P>
<P>
The soup, with slices of lotus root, was found intact in a
lacquer, three-legged pot among more than 1,000 luxury articles
buried with the wife of a minister of Changsha State in the early
Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-24 A.D.). The find was made 20 years
ago in Mawangdui, an eastern suburb of Changsha in Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
When the pot was taken to the city museum from the excavation
site, the slices of lotus root had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
"The fibre organization of the lotus root had rotted in the
long period of time, leaving only the outer structure which
vanished quickly after the inevitable shaking during the move,"
scientists explained.
</P>
<P>
The scientists inferred that few earthquake had shaken Changsha
in the last 2,000 years or else the slices of lotus root would
have vanished long ago. That theory was recently confirmed by
Chinese seismologists.
</P>
<P>
According to the seismologists, Changsha suffered only 11
earthquakes in the 1,700 years from 209 B.C. to 1980 A.D. None of
them was strong enough to cause obvious damage, or stronger than
4.75 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0060 </DOCNO>
