<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Help Vietnam Draw Plan Required by APEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will assist Vietnam
in drawing up an individual action plan required by the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), Malaysian Minister of
International Trade and Industry Rafidah Aziz said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia will also help Vietnam with the preparation of the
Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) list that is required
by the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) scheme, the minister told
reporters after her meeting with three Vietnamese ministers
accompanying President Tran Duc Luong on a visit here.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam became a member of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) in 1995 and is expected to be admitted into APEC
during the informal meeting of APEC leaders to be held here in
November.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said Malaysia's assistance in both areas will be
speeded up following her meeting with Vietnamese Minister of
Planning and Investment Tran Xuan Gia, Minister of Trade Truong
Dinh Tyuen and Industrial Minister Dang Vu Chu.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is the seventh largest investor in Vietnam. As of
December 31, 1997, Vietnam had approved 64 Malaysian projects with
a total capital outlay of 1.35 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total trade between the two countries in 1997 stood at 1.356
billion ringgit (about 358.73 million dollars) compared to 1.191
billion ringgit (about 315.08 million dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tran Duc Luong arrived here Monday afternoon for a three-day
visit, the first by a Vietnamese head of state since the two
countries established diplomatic ties in 1973.  
</P>
</TEXT>
