<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Macao External Trade Brisk in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Macao's imports and exports
business saw a brisk increase in 1997 despite an economic
slowdown, achieving a record trade surplus of 526 million patacas
(about 65.75 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Macao had reported trade deficits for years, but that reversed
in 1997. The latest figures from the Macao Census and Statistics
Department show that the value of exported goods reached 17.1
billion patacas (about 2.1375 billion dollars), up 7.7 percent
from that in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The value of imports was 16.6 billion patacas (about 2.075
billion dollars), up 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sharp increase in exports was due mainly to a surge in the
exports of garments and textile goods, which accounted for 85
percent of all exports last year.
</P>
<P>
That indicates Macao's exports have become increasingly
dependent on garments and textile goods, which mainly went to the
United States and the European Union, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The traditional export items, like toys, cement, machinery and
equipment, have been gradually dying out as their proportion
dropped to the minimum.
</P>
<P>
Sales to the United States rose by 1.3 billion patacas (about
162.5 million dollars), up 20.8 percent from 1996. The exports to
the European Union climbed 5.2 percent, an increase of 34.5
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the economic slowdown starting three years ago have
hit Macao's consumption. Although Macao bought more capital goods,
fuel and lubricating oil, raw materials and semi-finished goods,
the imports of consumer goods last year dropped 0.2 percent
compared with 1996.
</P>
<P>
Most of Macao's imported goods came from the Asian-Pacific
region, which supplied about 80 percent of the imports. While
goods from China's inland grew 24.2 percent, from Taiwan 9.6
percent and from South Korea 0.9 percent, the imports from Japan,
Hong Kong and Australia dropped as much as 15.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Macao bought 11 percent more goods from the United
States in 1997, but imports from the European Union declined six
percent.
</P>
<P>
A leading economic sector for Macao, external trade will most
likely suffer a blow in 1998 as there is no indication the
financial turmoil in Asia is ending, experts predict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
