<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Air Cargo Import Throughput Surges in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The volume of inbound cargo
passing through Kai Tak International Airport surged by 25.2
percent to 50,558 tons in February this year compared with the
same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released by the Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals
Limited (HACTL) here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Charter, managing director of the air cargo operator,
attributed the increase to an unusual rise in the quantities of
fresh fruit and seafood imported from Thailand last month.
</P>
<P>
"We think this is due to the weaker baht and possibly
alternative food sources because of the bird flu scare," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, in the long term, "we would expect the growth in
imports to be more gradual, month-on-month and without such
striking surges," he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that total air cargo handled by the HACTL
in February amounted to 104,992 tons, 10.3 percent more than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
This includes a fall of 1 percent to 40,050 tons in export
cargo and a 0.1-percent increase to 14,384 tons in transshipment
goods.
</P>
<P>
A modest increase of 3.1 percent has also been registered in
air freight throughput so far this year over a year ago, according
to the figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
