<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Design Contracts for HK's West Rail Project Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kowloon-Canton Railway
Corporation (KCRC) signed here on Tuesday five contracts totaling
one billion HK dollars (128.2 million U.S. dollars) for the
detailed design of Hong Kong's giant West Rail project.
</P>
<P>
KCRC Chairman K.Y. Yeung described the signing of the contracts
as a big step forward for the project.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good news not only to the people of Hong Kong whom
West Rail will serve, but also to those in the design and
construction industry," Yeung said at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The start of the West Rail Phase I project will certainly be a
stimulant to the industry in view of the slowdown of the local
economy and the near completion of the new airport, he said.
</P>
<P>
More contracts for West Rail will be awarded later this year as
the project moves forward. After the railway scheme is approved
by the Executive Council (ExCo) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region around September this year, the KCRC will be
able to award the first construction contract for West Rail --
the design and build contract for one of the two major tunnels --
in the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The detailed design works under the five contracts are expected
to be completed early next year.
</P>
<P>
The ExCo has endorsed a draft Project Agreement between the
KCRC and the government on the implementation of the West Rail
project. The two-phase project, when completed, will provide
railway links between urban Kowloon and the northwestern part of
the "New Territories," where population is growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
It is also designed to provide cross-boundary passenger and
freight services by connecting the railway network in Shenzhen of
South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Phase I of the project is scheduled to be put into operation
before the end of 2003, with an estimated total cost of 64 billion
HK dollars (8.21 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Detailed arrangements for Phase II are still under study and
discussion by the KCRC and the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
