<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Economy Maintains Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
commercial center, maintained steady economic growth during
January and February, according the municipal statistics
department.
</P>
<P>
The city's total GDP for the first two months of the year stood
at 48 billion yuan, up 7.7 percent on the 1997 period, with added
value for the industrial sector standing at 700 million yuan and
agricultural sector at 23.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The service sector's added value rose by 12.1 percent to 24
billion yuan and accounted for 50 percent of the city's total GDP.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded and township enterprises recorded an increased
proportion of GDP. The total industrial output for the two sectors
stood at 77 billion yuan, up eight percent on the 1997
period. Overseas-funded enterprises recorded a 14 percent increase
in industrial output value, with the figure for township
enterprises standing at 16.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city's retail sales volume for the period ended at 24.4
billion yuan, up 6.8 percent. Rapid increases were recorded for
retail sales of clothing, motorcycles, aquatic products, air
conditioners, color television sets and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's period export volume grew by 5.3 percent to 2.12
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The local consumer price index ended at 103.9, with the retails
price index of 96.8, 1.5 percentage points lower than the national
average for the period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
