<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Help Mozambique in Probe of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government pledged to provide Mozambican authorities with
whatever assistance they required in their gun smuggling
investigations of Foreign Affairs official Robert Mcbride, the
Business Day reported.
</P>
<P>
A top-level delegation led by South African Safety and
Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi Monday met the Mozambican
interior minister and the deputy foreign minister to discuss the
case of Mcbride.
</P>
<P>
South Africa confirmed that the two governments were of "one
mind" on the need for a thorough investigation into the matter,
the report quoted a statement issued after the meeting as saying.
</P>
<P>
South Africa pledged not to interfere in the due process of
Mozambican law, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
But it would "willingly give" Mozambican authorities any
assistance they needed, because it was "just as interested" in
the outcome of the case, it said.
</P>
<P>
Mcbride, a South African foreign affairs director in charge of
the Asian desk, is now in jail for the seventh day in Mozambique
Tuesday after being arrested for suspected arms dealing last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Star paper report said the high-level delegation, including
South African Police Service (SAPS) Commissioner George Fivaz,
Secret Service director-general Billy Masetla and South Africa's
ambassador to the Organization of African Unity Welile Nhlapo,
had attempted to persuade Mozambican authorities to swiftly
charge or release Mcbride.
</P>
<P>
It said Mufamadi would brief President Nelson Mandela and his
deputy Thabo Mbeki Tuesday on the controversy surrounding the
case.
</P>
<P>
A Mozambican judge has ruled that Mcbride be held until the
police are ready to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy Foreign Minister Aziz Pahad will fly to
Maputo Tuesday for further discussions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
