<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America Launches New Consumer Internet Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Bank of America, the second
largest bank holding company in the United States, has launched a
new consumer Internet service, targeting at home buyers.
</P>
<P>
The new HomeWorth Service, an interactive tool to the bank's
Web site, allows consumers to obtain home sales and price
information, along with other data, for specific properties and
general neighborhoods located throughout the country's 21 states.
</P>
<P>
Information includes sales date, sales price, square footage,
year built, number of bedrooms and bathrooms and other property
features.
</P>
<P>
Consumers can order a more detailed online report listing up to
30 percent property sales that were completed in the last 12
months within a half-mile radius of the address they entered in
the system.
</P>
<P>
Visitors can first access the bank's Web site and from there
click on the HomeWorth logo to access the service. From the bank's
award-winning Web site visitors can obtain information about home
equity loans, as well as an online mortgage application form,
current mortgage interest and information about how to set up and
finance a home office.
</P>
<P>
The San Francisco-based Bank of America, through its martgage
residential lending unit, is one of the largest mortgage lenders
and mortgage services in the United States. It originated more
than 16 billion U.S. dollars in home loans during 1997. As of
December 31, 1997, the bank had a mortgage serving portfolio of
almost 90 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials expect the new service to be popular with
consumers who are interested in applying for a home equity loan,
refinancing their existing mortgage, or examining their property
tax assessment compareed with equivalent properties in their
neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
