<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to rise
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) gained 16.47 points to close at 1621.26 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said stocks finished higher with several property
stocks and blue chip stocks chalking up the biggest price gains on
moderate institutional buying. Strong demand for a real estate
project by Keppel Land revived interest in property issues, they
said.
</P>
<P>
But they were quick to add that the standoff between the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Indonesia and uncertainty
about whether Indonesia will be implementing a currency board plan
continued to weigh down on sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 339 million units, valued
at 592.72 million Singapore dollars (about 368.15 million U.S.
dollars). Advances overtook declines by 224 to 107, while 280
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded stock as it
registered a turnover of 83.88 million units. It was followed by
IPC Corporation which had 18.16 million shares traded. Renong Bhd
was next with 13.68 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Jardine Matheson Holdings (JMH) 400 led the gainers of the day
as it rose by 40 cents to finish at 4.9 U.S. dollars. DBS
(Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign, Elec and F&AMP;N increased by
30 cents each to end at 12.6 Singapore dollars, 6.15 U.S. dollars
and 7 Singapore dollars respectively. OCBC (Overseas Chinese
Banking Corporation) Foreign was up by 25 cents to close at 8.75
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 and M. Banking 200 shared the top
spot on the losers' list as each of them declined by 20 cents to
end at 36.6 and 5.4 Singapore dollars respectively. Robinson and
VICOM fell by 15 cents each to close at 5.1 and 0.4 Singapore
dollars respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
