<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders to Bid Farewell to Masire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) will meet in Gaborone
Wednesday to bid farewell to Botswanan President Ketumile Masire
before his retirement on March 31.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) Tuesday quoted informed
sources as reporting that the 13 presidents
will arrive in Gaborone, capital of Botswana, to participate
in a ceremony and a banquet to bid their colleague farewell.
</P>
<P>
Part of the ceremony will see Masire planting a tree at the
SADC House, headquarters of the organization, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
SADC information spokesman Kgosinkwe Moesi ruled out SADC
leaders discussing business matters during their one-day stay,
saying "This is not a working meeting."
</P>
<P>
Masire, 72, is to step down on March 31 after being at the
helm of Botswana for the past 18 years. Prior to that, he was
vice-president for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
Masire took over the presidency on the death in 1980 of
Seretse Khama, who ruled Botswana since independence from Britain
in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Masire, a former primary school teacher and part-time farmer,
served as SADC chairman from 1980 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to his leadership, Botswana has been in a sound
economic condition. Since the discovery of diamonds in the early
1970s, Botswana has been transformed from a barren desert into
one of the richest countries on the African continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
