<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President to Meet U.N. Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will meet Thursday with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan who is
due in Cairo Wednesday on his first visit to Egypt since he took
helm at the world organization on January 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss a number of important issues, mainly the
Mideast peace process, the latest developments of the
situation in Iraq and relations between Egypt and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Ahram quoted well-informed diplomatic
sources at the U.N. as saying that Mubarak's talks with Annan will
focus on the U.N. role in pushing forward the peace process and
the importance of activating its role in quest of clearing the
Middle East of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
They will also exchange views on the issue of U.N.-imposed
sanctions on Libya, the situation in Somalia and other issues.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit here, Annan will hold talks
Wednesday with Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid the latest regional and
international developments and envisaged U.N. reform.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, who will also visit Syria, Lebanon, Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule area and Jordan on a nine-day Mideast
trip, reportedly carries a specific U.S. peace plan to
breathe life into the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The new peace initiative to be unveiled by U.S. President Bill
Clinton is aimed at unblocking the peace logjam through direct
U.S. involvement, U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Bill Richardson
told the London-based daily Al Hayat.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that Annan, with a deal at hand to ease the
Iraq-U.N. arms inspection crisis, will confer with regional
leaders the implementation of the U.N resolutions on the
decades-long Arab-Israeli conflicts and cooperation between these
countries and the world body.
</P>
<P>
Annan, a Ghanadian, who had been working with the United
Nations for 30 years, is the first U.N. chief to assume the office
from inside.
</P>
<P>
On New Year's Day in 1997, Annan, U.N. under-secretary-general
at that time, replaced former secretary-general Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, an Egyptian who retired at the end of his five-year
term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
