<HEADLINE> S. African Truckers to Intensify Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's transport
sector faces further disruption as strike by truck drivers
nationwide picks up momentum Tuesday and bus drivers plan to join
them in two days' time.
</P>
<P>
A freight union spokesman predicted a 100 percent disruption
in the road and freight sector Tuesday as seven unions, which
represent more than 40,000 workers across the country, planned to
intensify their protests to back up their wage demands, The Star
paper reported.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 workers are expected to gather in Johannesburg
Tuesday and march to the industry's National Bargaining Council
to hand in a memorandum of their demands.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of truck drivers embarked on a strike Monday in
Johannesburg following last Friday's deadlock in labor-management
talks over wage increases and other benefits. There were reports
of violence during their march across the city.
</P>
<P>
The workers rejected employers' final subsistence allowances
and minimum wage offers ranging from 11.5 to 18 percent, saying
that their job, which means a lot hours on the road, high risks
of being hijacked and little time to be with their families,
deserves higher pay and better working conditions.
</P>
<P>
A parallel meeting in the Commission for Conciliation,
Mediation and Arbitration, the first since the parties
deadlocked, is scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the industrial action may peak on Thursday
when more than 20,000 bus drivers stage a strike in major parts
of the country if wage negotiations fail. The bus drivers are
demanding a 10.5 percent wage rise and employers are offering 7.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The strike could affect bus commuter services to more than 6.2
million people around the country, including the major
metropolitan centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
