<HEADLINE> Nation Group in Kenya Goes into TV, Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nation Group in Kenya, a
leading publishing organization in east and central Africa, has
acquired a majority stake in East African Television Network Ltd.
(EATN) through its wholly-owned subsidiary, African Broadcasting
Ltd. (ABL).
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Tuesday quoted Wilfred Kiboro, the
Group's Chief Executive, as saying on Monday that radio and
television broadcasts were expected to begin in the second half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The broadcasting would begin in Nairobi and then extend
coverage on a stage-by-stage basis throughout Kenya, he said.
</P>
<P>
It would not only benefit Kenyans, but also enhance east
African co-operation as the first step in the group's plans to
establish broadcast stations in Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda,
said the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
EATN becomes the newest broadcaster in a list of radio and
television stations in the country including the Kenya Television
Network, Stellavision, Capital FM, Metro East, BBC FM Radio,
M-Net and the Kenya Broadcasting Corporation's various television
and radio outlets.
</P>
<P>
EATN obtained authority from Kenyan Ministry of Information
and Broadcasting on August 9, 1996, to transmit over the whole
country. Last year the Kenya Posts and Tele-communications
Corporation assigned it six TV and radio frequencies.
</P>
<P>
Nation Printers and Publishes is a 55 percent publicly owned
company, with some 8,000 Kenyan shareholders. The principal
shareholder of the group is His Highness the Aga Khan, leader of
the Shia Muslim Ismaili community who founded the nation
newspapers in 1960.  
</P>
</TEXT>
