<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Flying Horse Stranded on Way to Zanzibar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Tanzanian cruise ship
with some 110 passengers aboard got stranded Monday on her way
one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
Port sources said Tuesday that the Flying Horse, a luxury
passenger boat, was just passing through the Magogoni Creek,
about 3 kilometers from Dar es Salaam, when she was pierced
underneath, allowing in water and starting sinking.
</P>
<P>
"A strange sound under the water was heard and then the vessel
started swaying on one side causing panic among the passengers
who started running randomly for safety," they said.
</P>
<P>
However, calm was restored a few minutes after the operators
diverted the vessel to shallow waters and rescue boats were
coming to answer a SOS call.
</P>
<P>
"All the passengers were evacuated to safety in boats and
tugs", the sources said, confirming that the passengers were
refunded their fares and the Flying Horse was still in the
shallow waters till Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Lying in the western part of the Indian Ocean, a trip to the
Zanzibar Island is about two-hour drive by luxury ships from the
mainland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
