<HEADLINE> Preferences for Foreign Goods Outweigh Actual Purchases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey indicated that a
mere 8.2 percent Chinese respondents purchase foreign goods on a
regular basis, with a much higher percentage indicating a
preference for foreign brands.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 5,138 families in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou
revealed that 33.1 percent of respondents occasionally purchase
foreign goods, with some 36.1 percent rarely and 21.2 percent
never purchasing related items.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of age groups revealed that people over 55
represented the highest proportion of respondents expressing
dislike for foreign brands.
</P>
<P>
In terms of professional status, executives working in the
non-state and private sectors were the most avid shoppers for
foreign goods, followed by executives working for state
enterprises. The figures indicated that higher preference levels
are determined by higher income levels.
</P>
<P>
Some 87.8 percent of respondents cited better quality as the
reason for purchasing foreign brand names, with 59.3 percent
noting their hesitancy to purchase same things on higher price.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of respondents indicated the relatively
high-level availability of foreign goods on the Chinese market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
