<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Ministers Asked to Donate to Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
Tuesday asked all his ministers to donate their one-year basic
salary to help the government's poverty alleviation program.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto himself pledged to donate his basic salary
and other allowances to the poverty alleviation program,
Minister/State Secretary Saadilah Mursyid told the press following
the first cabinet meeting of the newly-appointed ministers at the
Bina Graha here.
</P>
<P>
"I receive pension and that is enough for me. Therefore, I am
giving all my salary to the program," Soeharto, who chaired the
meeting, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official salary of a cabinet minister is around 4 million
rupiah (at present, one U.S. dollar equals 9,000 to 10,000 rupiah)
per month.
</P>
<P>
According to Soeharto, the fund may be used to help run small
food kiosks by people who have been laid off from their jobs
recently because of the current monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the one-hour meeting, Soeharto explained to his
ministers the country's latest economic situation and its
connection to the Washington-based International Monetary Fund
(IMF), Saadilah said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been hit badly by the monetary crisis since July
last year, with its currency, the rupiah, having lost about 80
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar. As a result of the
monetary turmoil, the country has been facing spiraling inflation,
growing unemployment and other serious economic and social
problems.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the economic difficulties, the Indonesian
government agreed in November last year to embrace IMF reforms in
return for a 43 billion U.S. dollar global aid package.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF delayed its second tranche worth 3 billion
dollars in assistance to Indonesia because of the so-called lack
of reforms in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Soeharto also asked all his ministers to
declare their personal wealth and that of their respective
spouses.
</P>
<P>
"All ministers were asked to itemize their personal wealth,
including properties and assets," Information Minister Alwi Dahlan
said.
</P>
<P>
Saadilah said all governors are also required to make the same
report to the president.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's seventh cabinet was formed last Saturday by
President Soeharto who was reelected to his seventh term of office
at the general session of the people's Consultative Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The 36-member cabinet will serve a five-year term from 1998 to
2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
