<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- France's far-right National Front (FN) is trying to lead
astray the most vulnerable elements of the rightwing opposition of
RPR and UDF in an operation of seduction.
</P>
<P>
The FN is making moderate proposals for shifting the votes it
has won in the regional elections to the opposition, in order to
sow seeds of trouble within the PRP and UDF, which have excluded
an alliance with the far-right.
</P>
<P>
-- Thirty years after the 1968 extreme-leftist movement in
France, the extreme-leftists of the country are now coming up as an
electoral force by winning 4.35 percent of the votes in the regional
elections on Sunday, against 1.2 percent they won six years ago.
</P>
<P>
The extreme-left Lutte Ouvriere will take 20 seats in regional
councils, half of them in the northern region of
Nord-Pas-de-Calais and in the Paris region, while another
extreme-left group the LCR will have three seats.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The far-right National Front will play the role of arbitrator
in the election of president in eight regional parliaments on
Friday. The FN president Jean-Marie Le Pen has made a minimum
proposal on socio-economic policy to the opposition RPR and UDF in
exchange for support.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party has warned the opposition against an
alliance with the FN.
</P>
<P>
-- Will Robin Cook, the British Foreign Secretary, walk the steps
of Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Cook seems determined to play an active role in saving the
Mideast peace process by deciding to visit the Arab part of
Jerusalem on Tuesday. 
