<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Economy Grows Only 1.9 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Israel's gross domestic product
(GDP) for 1997 rose 1.9 percent compared with the around 4 percent
in 1996, according to figures published by the Central Bureau of
Statistics (CBS) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure suggests that the recession of the Israel's economy
is deepening.
</P>
<P>
For the second half of 1997, there was a shrinking in
investments and a significant slowdown in activities in the
industrial and building sectors in Israel.
</P>
<P>
CBS said that the per capita GDP fell 0.5 percent in 1997 after
rising 1.8 percent in 1996 and 4.2 percent in 1995. The per capita
GDP for 1997 stood at 16,571 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The CBS noted that the decline in the product per capita is
worrisome. It has also become evident that per capita private
consumption rose only 0.9 percent in 1997, compared to 2.6 percent
in 1996 and 4.6 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Senior Finance Ministry officials were reportedly surprised by
the extent of the decline in investment and growth rate in the
second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
They estimated that there will be only 1 to 1.5 percent growth
in 1998, much less than the 3 percent set in the state budget.
</P>
<P>
CBS economists also noted that Israel's economic performance
this year is not as good as expected and January-February figures
do not indicate a revival in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
They attributed this to the economic adjustment policy of the
current government aimed at cutting overspending and privatization.
</P>
<P>
But others also pointed out that the stalled peace process is
another major reason hindering Israel's economic development,
resulting in sharp decline of foreign investments in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
