<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola to Produce Copper Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Motorola company announced
Monday that it has completed testing of its first silicon wafers
utilizing copper technology, which will lead to production later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Engineers at Motorola's Semiconductor Products Sector, based in
Austin, Texas, completed the testing wafers, and prototypes in
various applications were now underway, according to reports from
the company.
</P>
<P>
In September last year, Motorola said it had developed a
technique that replaced aluminum wiring with copper interconnects
in integrated circuits, resulting in smaller and faster chips.
</P>
<P>
Called a dual-inlaid metallization technique, the process takes
advantage of copper's higher conductivity than aluminum to provide
smaller, thinner interconnects. Copper also has greater
resistance to electro-migration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
