<HEADLINE> S.Lanka Parliament Debates Civil Rights Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's parliament Tuesday
began a debate on a motion to deprive former minister Wijepala
Mendis of the United National Party (UNP) of his civil rights for
seven years and expel him from Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mendis, who is the Chief Opposition Whip, was found guilty last
March of abuse and misuse of power by a Special Presidential
Commission which recommended that he be made subject to civil
disability for seven years and be expelled from Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The law requires a majority of two-thirds to pass the motion,
which government will not be able to muster without the support of
the main opposition UNP.
</P>
<P>
The debate, which was broadcast live over the Sri Lankan
broadcasting Corporation (SLBC), started at 10:00 a.m. (local
time). But the UNP is staging a boycott of Parliament for one
month from March 3 protesting against the erosion of democratic
institutions.
</P>
<P>
In presenting the motion which stood in the name of Prime
Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike, the Leader of the House Ratnasiri
Wickremanayake said there was no malice against anyone in moving
the motion and all they wanted to do was to clean up society.
</P>
<P>
Ceylon Workers Congress R. Yoganathan said his community
(estate workers of Indian origin) had suffered for forty years
without civil rights. They believed nobody should be deprived of
civil rights and nobody had the right to remove the civil rights
from anybody else. It was worse than a murder sentence.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of Planning Samaraweera Weerawanni and Deputy
Minister of Transport Athauda Seneviratne also supported the
motion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
