<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Debt to Hit 50 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' foreign debt is
projected to breach the 50 billion U.S. dollar mark this year, as
the government has embarked on fresh borrowings to beef up its
foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
Documents from the central bank indicate that the country's
outstanding external debt would reach 51.9 billion dollars by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest official figures show that the country's foreign
debt stood at 48.2 billion dollars as of last September.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to build up its foreign reserves from
the current 9.3 billion dollars to at least 12 billion dollars, or
19 months worth of imports, by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
With the planned new borrowings, the country's foreign debt
would exceed the 50 billion dollar level, banking officials said.
</P>
