<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Stronger Baht Arouses Mixed Sentiments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai baht Monday rebounded to
a four-month high of 39.80 baht to the U.S. dollar before slipping
slightly. But the stronger baht aroused mixed sentiments among the
country's exporters.
</P>
<P>
The baht slipped slightly after reaching 39.80 to close at
40.40/40.60 compared with 41.00/41.20 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers and analysts attributed the appreciation of the baht to
the successful visit to the United States by Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai.
</P>
<P>
Besides, good indicators in the market also helped the currency
to strengthen. Among them were the announcement by the Customs
Department that exports were up 90 percent year on year in baht
terms and 14 percent in dollar terms, and last week's fourth
consecutive monthly current account surplus.
</P>
<P>
However, the currency's rise in turn worried exporters, who
were afraid of a rapid appreciation would hurt the industry and
cut competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Vanida Kulkumthorn, executive director of the Thai Garment
Manufacturers Association, said the quick appreciation of the baht
over the past two to three trading days has already affected
exporters, especially in sectors which have high import contents
such as textiles.
</P>
<P>
The currency fluctuations made it difficult to quote new
contracts due to greater uncertainty over the currency's value,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Most contracts written earlier, which take four to five months
to fulfill, were based on 45 baht per dollar. Under those
conditions, exporters lose money when the baht appreciates
significantly.
</P>
<P>
Vanida also said that rapid currency fluctuations will also
hurt exporters' liquidity as a stronger baht means higher prices
for Thai products in the world markets, which will reduce the
competitiveness of the country's exporters.
</P>
<P>
According to foreign bank officials, exporters who have foreign
debts will benefit from the situation. But they will also get less
export income at the same time.
</P>
<P>
For the economy as a whole, the appreciation of baht is mostly
welcomed, since a strengthening baht will lead to increased
confidence among foreign investors and the return of capital.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand Governor Chaiyawat Wilbulswasdi said the
increased stability of the baht could allow interest rates to
gradually come down in the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor said lending rates would likely
reduce to around 15 to 16 percent from the current 20 percent,
while deposit rates to 13 percent from 16 percent now.
</P>
<P>
Thai businesses have complained bitterly of high interest
rates, which they say are driving them into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the baht's rise, analysts warn that it could be the
lull before the storm as foreign debt repayments are expected to
come due in April, June and July.
</P>
<P>
So far, it is hard to predict what level the baht should stand
at. The country must be patient to follow the direction of the
baht's move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Welcomes Sugar Quota Increase to US Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Australia will be allowed to
export an extra 16,000 tons of sugar to the United States this
year following an increase in the U.S. sugar import quota,
Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This is welcome news for Australian sugar exporters," Fisher
said.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in Australian access results from a 200,000 ton
increase in the U.S. global import quota for the year ending
September, 1998," the deputy prime minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Australia is the United States' fourth largest source of
imported sugar, behind the Dominican Republic, Brazil, and the
Philippines. The market access for Australia this year will now be
109,699 tons.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said Australia remained concerned over the limited
access offered to the U.S. market, and that Australia's original
quota for 1997-1998 had been cut by 40 percent from the previous
financial year.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the U.S. global quota followed a periodic
assessment of the U.S. stocks-use ratio for sugar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
