<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Exposes Worsening Economic Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 17 (Xinhua) -- One fifth of Palestinians are
living in poverty as the Palestinian economy has worsened since
the 1993 signing of peace deals with Israel, a survey said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out by Palestinian Economics and Trade
Ministry and World Bank, said that about 500,000, or 19.1 percent,
of the 2.5 million Palestinian population are living under the
poverty line of 650 U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The study attributed the worsening situation to the frequent
closures Israel has imposed on the Palestinian self-rule areas,
which restricted the movement of goods and people and caused a
slowdown in the private sector and labor market.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Palestinians who worked in Israel have
been affected by the closures. The number of laborers working in
Israel dropped from 116,000 in 1993 to 28,000 in 1997, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, unemployment in the West Bank and Gaza Strip has
almost doubled since 1993, rising to 28.4 percent in 1997 from
18.2 percent in 1995. World Bank officials said this is
considered to be the highest unemployment in the world.
</P>
<P>
The closures have also pushed up the cost of transporting
goods and reduced the volume and value of trade. Between 1992 and
1995, revenues fell to 48 percent of gross national product (GNP)
from 61 percent and exports dropped from 14 percent of GNP to 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
Israel meanwhile insisted that the Palestinian economy is
improving due to Israeli efforts. Yaacov Orr, Government
Coordinator in the territories, told the Knesset (Parliament)
Monday that there is no limit on the number of Palestinian
workers entering Israel and there is increased trade between
Israel and the territories.
</P>
<P>
Orr said Israel would continue making efforts to improve the
Palestinian economy, because the improved feeling of well-being
would reduce the ability of terror organizations to recruit
activists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wise Not to Sponsor Resolution on China's Human Rights: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The decision of the United States
not to sponsor the resolution on China's human rights is wise,
said Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao at a regular
news conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the US decision not to sponsor the
resolution at the Geneva meeting of the U.N. Human Rights
Commission, Zhu said that this will serve the healthy and stable
development of relations between China and the US.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that, on the issue of human rights, China
advocates consistently that China and the US should conduct
dialogue on the basis of equality and mutual respect, instead of
confrontation. 
