<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed higher Tuesday in Sydney after strong performances across
industrial stocks, boosted by a surge on Wall Street overnight and
improving sentiment in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co's Grant Williams said investors were flocking to
the quality stocks, with Australia's largest telecommunications
company Telstra an outstanding performer.
</P>
<P>
"There was a huge demand there today for Telstra shares, it
just seems to keep on going."
</P>
<P>
Williams said the local bourse could also be fueled by
anticipation of further rises on Wall Street later in the week.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 37.2 points higher at 2,767.1,
just off its intraday high of 2,769.6.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished up 9.4 points at 1,172.0 and
the all industrials index was 71 points stronger at 4,763.3.
</P>
<P>
Industrial stocks were boosted by a further 3.5 percent gain in
News Corp and a bullish performance by Telstra shares.
</P>
<P>
News Corp closed 36 cents higher at 10.45 Australian dollars
and its preferred shares were 36.5 cents, or 4.3 percent, stronger
at 8.875 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking index was 91 points stronger at 5,685.8 with rises
across the sector.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank led the way with a 35 cent gain to
21.25 Australian dollars, ANZ bank was up 28.5 cents at 10.36
Australian dollars, Commonwealth rose 29.4 cents to 18.044
Australian dollars and Westpac was 10 cents stronger at 10.58
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, stocks were mixed, with leader BHP
17.5 cents stronger at 15.83 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto was up 24 cents to 19.40 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index added 2.8 points to end the day at 1,109.6.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney, gold bullion closed at 294.15 US dollars, up 10
cents on Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 323.54 million shares worth 638.3
million US dollars, with rises of 685 outpacing falls of 497.
</P>
