<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Projects Growth in Civilian Aircraft Fleet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Growing demand for air
transportation will require China to increase its civilian
aircraft fleet by 1,591 units for the period between 1997-2016,
with related purchases involving total funds of 75.94 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest Report on Civilian Aircraft Requirements in the
Chinese Market (1997-2016), published by the China Aviation
Industry, predicts that the country's airliner fleet reach 1,921
units by the year 2016.
</P>
<P>
China had accepted delivery of 86 new aircraft by the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
The report, which considers various factors, predicts that
China's air transportation volume will reach 229.4 billion
person/km by 2016, up 3.1-fold on 1996. The expected average
annual growth rate of 11.9 percent will exceed increases of the
country's gross national product and the worldwide air
transportation volume.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for China's share of the worldwide air
transportation volume to grow from 2.4 percent to 6.7 percent over
the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
New aircraft will replace some 188 airliners in China's
existing aircraft fleet which will be removed from service over
the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
The report has been published on an annual basis since 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
