<HEADLINE> Fredericks Gets Apology over Missing Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) - Namibian sprinter Frankie
Fredericks received apology on Monday from a Commonwealth Games
Federation official over his bronze medal that has yet to arrive.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Games Federation secretary David Dixon said in a
BBC radio program that Fredericks will get his medal which he won
after being moved up to the bronze medal slot in the 100 meters
sprint at the 1994 Commonwealth Games.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's Horace Dove-Edwin, who had originally finished
second, was disqualified following a positive drug test.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks did not receive his medal and had threatened to
boycott this year's Games in Kuala Lumpur if it did not arrive
soon.
</P>
<P>
"It is a complete oversight that the medals were not adjusted,"
Dixon said. "Mr Fredericks will get his medal, even if we have to
get a new one from the engravers."  
