<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Extends 600 Million Dollars to Thai Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Export-Import Bank of Japan
and 14 other leading Japanese banks have signed a contract to
provide 600 million U.S. dollars to help Thailand's cash-strapped
exporters.
</P>
<P>
The loan, to be guaranteed by the Thai Finance Ministry,
carries a term of five years with a three-year grace period, the
Bangkok Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The loan, to be on-lent partly in yen, will carry an average
2.65 percent annual interest.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said at the signing
ceremony Monday that the Industrial Finance Corporation of
Thailand (IFCT) and the Export-Import (EXIM) Bank of Thailand will
each receive half of the loan.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be re-lent by the IFCT and EXIM bank to
exporters, Japanese subsidiary companies, and companies
participating in joint ventures with Japanese firms, which require
medium- and long-term loans or working capital.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin also said the first disbursement of the loan, totaling
40 billion yen or 300 million dollars, will arrive by the end of
this month, and second between August and September.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese vice-minister of finance Yasuhisha
Shiozaki, who also attended Monday's signing ceremony, said the
loans showed the Japanese government's strong support of
Thailand's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the yen loans were the first step toward
encouraging yen-denominated trading in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that "internationalizing" the Japanese currency would
require more capital to be raised in yen, with the latest loans to
Thailand a good start.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the largest investor in Southeast Asia and one of the
biggest creditors in the region. However, regional trade and
finance transactions have long been dominated by the U.S. dollar.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
