<HEADLINE> Wellington Leads New Zealand in Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Wellington region led New
Zealand in economic growth last year despite the impact of the
Asian financial crisis which began to hit the country in the
latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The local Evening Post newspaper Tuesday quoted a National Bank
survey as saying that the region's economy grew 4.2 percent in
1997, nearly twice as fast as all of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The region has outperformed the national economy for the past
two years after seven years during which it lagged behind the
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that real estate sales rose 4 percent in the
Wellington region last year, while sales nationally dipped;
Consumer confidence was the highest in the country; New housing
starts climbed 4.7 percent compared with an 8 percent decline
nationwide; Retails sales increased 4.4 percent against a 5.5
percent fall across New Zealand; And employment grew faster than
the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the short-term prospects for the
region remain bright, thanks to the opening of the new Museum of
New Zealand which is expected to attract more tourists to
Wellington.
</P>
<P>
The power failure in the country's largest Auckland also helped
the economy in Wellington, as some companies in Auckland have
shifted their staff to the capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
