<HEADLINE> Measure Taken to Help Foreign Firms Avoid Unauthorized Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The capital of northwest China's
Gansu Province has offered 22 overseas-funded enterprises
"fee-charging supervision cards" as part of the effort to fight
the practice of random fee collections.
</P>
<P>
According to the city government's regulations, any government
department must fill in related items on the card before charging
fees, while inspection and supervision departments will do
the check accordingly in a bid to stop unauthorized charges, which
have long plagued the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the latest steps the city has taken to improve
the investment environment in Lanzhou. By the end of 1997, Lanzhou
had approved the establishment of 1,146 overseas-backed ventures
involving 1.55 billion U.S. dollars. 
