<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Diversion Project Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A Yellow River water diversion
project is going well and bringing benefits to farmers in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The project, begun in 1996, aims to develop 133,000 hectares of
arable land along the Yellow River and help a million impoverished
farmers in the region's southern mountainous areas resettle.
</P>
<P>
By last year, a 32-kilometer water aqueduct and canal was
completed, diverting water from the river up to the Xihaigu
mountainous areas to irrigate 120 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Trial irrigation on nearly 100 hectares of farmland in two
counties has been successful, making it possible to promote
water-efficient agriculture in the area.
</P>
<P>
After the first phase of the project is completed at a cost of
2.33 billion yuan in static investment, more than 3,300 hectares
of wasteland will have been irrigated by the end of this year, as
well as infrastructure and living conditions for the resettlement
of 25,000 farmers will be improved.
</P>
<P>
By now, more than 100 million yuan has already been spent on
the project, and this year a loan from Kuwait of 33 million
U.S. dollars will be put into use. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
