<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Economy to Slow Down Sharply This Year: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy will slow
down sharply this year, although the country is benefiting from
its strong underlying economic fundamentals, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In an appraisal of Singapore's economic development and
policies released here, the IMF Executive Directors said
Singapore's strong fundamentals had helped to shield the country's
financial market from the regional turmoil and had allowed foreign
investors to remain confident about Singapore's short- and
medium-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
The strong fundamentals included its high saving rate, large
fiscal and external current account surpluses, flexible markets,
robust reserve position, and high standard of regulation and
supervision for domestic financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, the Directors observed that there are still downside
risks associated with the regional economic slowdown, and that,
even in the absence of further unexpected regional spill-overs,
growth in Singapore will slow down sharply this year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said that given Singapore's circumstances, it is
appropriate for the authorities to reduce over the medium term the
government's operating surplus and, in order to do that, corporate
and personal income tax rates should be reduced in next year's
budget alongside the intended increases in development expenditure
to provide some fiscal stimulus to the economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Directors also endorsed the Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS)'s "intention to maintain an easier monetary policy
stance as long as the inflationary outlook remains subdued."
</P>
<P>
But they added that the authorities need to "review the stance
at frequent intervals to ensure that inflation remains low."
</P>
<P>
The IMF's board also supported Singapore's move to a more
flexible exchange rate policy given volatility in Asian
currencies. But they added that an appreciation of the Singapore
dollar would be appropriate once the regional situation stabilizes
and output returns to its potential level.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the IMF said, continued restructuring of the
economy into higher value-added sectors and upgrading of the skill
level of the workforce were essential to safeguard Singapore's
competitiveness over the medium term.
</P>
<P>
The IMF Directors also urged the Singapore authorities to
increase transparency regarding holdings of government assets
abroad and the net open forward position of the MAS, and to
broaden the coverage and to improve the breakdown of the public
sector accounts so as to facilitate economic analysis.
</P>
<P>
The MAS said in a statement on Tuesday that the Singapore
government "welcomes the IMF's endorsement of its macroeconomic
management during the past year under difficult conditions of
regional financial market turbulence."
</P>
<P>
It also stressed that the authorities "will continue to manage
the Singapore dollar flexibly against a trade-weighted basket of
currencies. The primary objective of our exchange rate policy
remains unchanged, namely to maintain price stability."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
