<HEADLINE> Kenya Moves to Curb Dumping of Untaxed Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
announced tough measures to curb dumping of petroleum products
which are destined for export and diverted to sell at black
market in Kenya, the East African Standard reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Energy Minister Chris Okemo as
saying Monday that the government had banned export of
petroleum by road to Somalia, Sudan and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
All exports of petroleum products to Uganda and Tanzania will
now be limited to only licensed marketers, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The measures to curb the oil dumping include the establishment
of a special police unit to enhance the Transit Monitoring Unit
of the Kenya Revenue Authority.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police who have launched a countrywide operation to
round up illegal petrol dealers, said that more than 400 people
had been arrested in the on-going operation.
</P>
<P>
A senior police source said, "So far over 80,000 liters of
super petrol, 210 liters of regular petrol and 32,000 liters of
diesel had been seized."
</P>
<P>
The operation on illegal oil dealers followed a directive made
by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi on March 6 that those
involved in the oil racket be rounded up.
</P>
<P>
the president said that oil destined for export was diverted
to sell in the black market and the government lost a large
amount of money through unpaid taxes.
</P>
<P>
About 45 of those arrested had been taken to court and other
50 cases were still pending before the court, said the police
source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
