<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City to Improve Minimum Standards of Living </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, plans to further improve its policies
to ensure minimum standards of living for poor families in urban and
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in May, all local people living below the poverty
line will receive subsidiaries from the government, instead
of their work units.
</P>
<P>
The city adopted the bottom-line policy for urban residents in
July of 1995, and the poverty line for urban residents was raised
from the 200 yuan to 240 yuan a month in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since January of 1997, more than 10,000 rural people in the
suburbs have also been covered by a similar policy. A total of
5.41 million yuan has been spent for the purpose last year.
</P>
<P>
Beginning this year, the policy will cover all local people in
rural areas, while the bottom lines for rural people will be set
differently in three categories: 100 yuan for poverty-stricken
areas, 120 yuan for common areas and 150 for well-off areas.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the subsidiaries will be shared by the city,
townships and villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
