<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Dealing with Issue of Migrant Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- More and more migrant workers
are having difficulty finding jobs in south China's Guangdong
Province, where a well-planned labor flow is preferred.
</P>
<P>
Local labor departments began last year to classify the labor
force and asking every potential employer to apply for the use of
laborers. They also required migrant workers to have employment
cards issued by labor departments.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the province has taken steps to guide
transient labor forces into an orderly flow, as fears arise that
an increasing influx of migrant laborers could bring negative
impact on local life.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that slightly more than 4 million laborers
found jobs with the help of labor departments, an increase of
500,000 over the previous year. And 95 percent of them had
employment cards.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the developed Pearl River Delta area accepted
100,000 surplus laborers from poor areas of neighboring Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, and Shenzhen employed more than 6,000
rural laborers from the mountainous Guizhou Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
