<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Office Rents in Vietnam's Capital City Fall by 30 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Office rents in Vietnam's capital
city of Hanoi have fallen at least 30 percent in recent weeks,
the Vietnam News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prices in downtown Hanoi have fallen to 30 US dollars per
square metre and 20 dollars per square metre elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The total demand on office rentals is now 11,000 square metres
out of a capacity of 60,000, with no change in the number of
tenants, the Vietnam News said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the cause of low occupancy rates is the slowdown
in investment and the overall economy resulting from the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in the first two months of
this year, the Vietnamese government licensed 24 foreign-backed
projects amounting to an investment of 926 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
