<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Meets Sinn Fein Leader Gerry Adams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
met with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams Monday night, hoping to push
the Northern Ireland peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
After a 15-minute talk with Clinton, Adams and the Sinn Fein
chief negotiator Martin McGuinness said their talk had focused on
positive discussions and praised the president for his commitment
to search for peace in the province.
</P>
<P>
As the head of the Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, Adams indicated that the talks would not achieve
his goal of an unified Ireland, but he would accept the outcome of
the current round of talks.
</P>
<P>
However he insisted: "Britain (should) accept the creation of
a rolling process, a transitional process, a bridge from today's
situation into a new beginning for all the people of Ireland."
</P>
<P>
Adams, McGuinness and leaders of other parties in Northern
Ireland are gathered in Washington for a St. Patrick's Day
reception at the White House on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The White House expects the present round of talks to achieve
some success. Clinton hopes the meeting could reach the outline
of an agreement, said the White House spokesman Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party peace talks, which began in June 1996, are
supposed to conclude in May. Negotiators hope a compromise on
governing Northern Ireland, which is acceptable to both its
Protestant majority and the large Catholic minority, can be
agreed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
