<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador to U.S. Presents Letter of Credence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The new Chinese Ambassador to
the United States, Li Zhaoxing, presented his Letter of Credence
to U.S. President Bill Clinton, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ambassador Li conveyed greetings from
President Jiang Zemin to President Clinton. In return, Clinton
congratulated his Chinese counterpart on his re-election as
president.
</P>
<P>
Li, former deputy foreign minister of China, said that during
President Jiang's successful state visit to the U.S. last fall,
both sides agreed to work toward the establishment of a
constructive strategic partnership in the interest of world peace
and development.
</P>
<P>
As President Clinton will return a visit to China this year at
the invitation of President Jiang, the ambassador expressed the
belief that the exchange of state visits by the two heads of state
will usher the Sino-U.S. relations into a new phase of development.
</P>
<P>
"It is the hope and conviction of the Chinese side that as long
as the two sides strictly abide by the principles enshrined in the
three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, implement the China-U.S. Joint
Statement in real earnest, enhance mutual understanding, expand
common ground and increase cooperation, they will be able to bring
a steadily developing Sino-U.S. relationship into the 21st
century," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Fully aware of the heavy responsibility upon him, the
ambassador pledged to do his utmost to develop bilateral relations
and enhance the friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, who decided to move his trip forward to
China to this summer, said that better relationships between the
two great countries is vital for the world peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the United States and China shared great interests
in Asia and the world as a whole, and he was looking forward to
visiting China and meeting once again with President Jiang in
joint efforts to further the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of China's "extraordinary economic
achievements" in recent years.
</P>
<P>
United States National Security Advisor Sandy Berger was
present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li arrived in the United States on March 11. He
served as China's permanent representative to the United Nations
before he became deputy foreign minister in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
