<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Encourages Firms to List on Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
plans to prompt more of its backbone enterprises to become listed
on the stock market in an effort to quench an investment thirst.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial official, priority will be given to
its 1,000 large state-owned companies and 120 group companies
which dominate Jiangsu's agriculture, energy, transportation, raw
material and high-tech industries to help promote the
development of machinery, electronics, chemical, automobile,
biochemical, new material and tourist industries.
</P>
<P>
A number of these companies engaged in industrial and
infrastructural sectors are expected to be allowed to list on
stock exchanges in Hong Kong, Singapore, Tokyo and New York for
overseas investment, said Li Sanyuan, a senior official from the
provincial securities regulatory office.
</P>
<P>
Stock market listings have helped raise 17.7 billion yuan for
38 companies in the province, according to Liu Jian, provincial
vice-governor. In 1996, 14 stocks were issued amassing 2.87
billion yuan; and, in 1997, 16 were issued accumulating 8.5
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Stocks issued by a number of well-performing companies from the
province have been trading well in the secondary markets of
Shanghai and Shenzhen, said Li.
</P>
<P>
He also said Jiangsu will set a faster pace in gaining overseas
finance, following its initial tryout in entering international
capitalization markets with five of the listed companies issuing
B-shares in Shanghai and three issuing H-shares in Hong Kong
raising 8.38 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
