<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Approved As New Premier by NPC Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing First Session of the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature,
this morning held its fifth plenary meeting, at which Zhu Rongji
was approved, by way of voting, as premier of the State Council,
the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also approved by voting Zhang Wannian and Chi
Haotian to be vice-chairmen of the Central Military Commission
(CMC), and Fu Quanyou, Yu Yongbo, Wang Ke and Wang Ruilin members
of the CMC.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yang and Han Zhubin were elected president of the Supreme
People's Court and procurator-general of the Supreme People's
Procuratorate respectively at today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
At 9 a.m., Hu Jintao, an executive chairman of the session's
Presidium, announced the beginning of today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
The session staff first read out two letters from Jiang Zemin,
president of the country and chairman of the CMC, nominating
respectively a candidate for the premiership and candidates for
the posts of CMC vice-chairmen and members.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Constitution stipulates that a candidate for the
State Council premiership should be nominated by state president
and that candidates for the posts of CMC vice-chairmen and members
nominated by chairman of the CMC. All nominations must be
submitted to the NPC for final decision.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 2,951 NPC deputies attending today's meeting
received four ballots in different colors, which were respectively
for the premier, CMC vice-chairmen and members, president of the
Supreme People's Court and procurator-general of the Supreme
People's Procuratorate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 86 Reservoirs, Dams Built in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 86 reservoirs and dams
have been built in Myanmar since 1988, irrigating 535,400 hectares
of farmland, official The New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the mainstay of Myanmar's economy, and paddy,
beans and pulses, cotton and sugarcane are the country's four
pillar crops.
</P>
<P>
The country maintained an average annual rice export of 463,750
tons in the last four-year plan period (1992-93 to 1995-96),
fetching 88 million U.S. dollars annually, 40 percent of the
country's foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's paddy production in the 1996-97 was 17.08 million
tons with 93,000 tons of rice exported.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of rice exports in the fiscal year and the
planned stop in the export in the current 1997-98 were seen as
giving priority to the domestic demand and the stabilization of
the internal rice market.
</P>
<P>
However, a total of 6.48 million hectares are being targeted to
be under paddy in the whole country to produce 20 million tons of
paddy for the current 1997-98 fiscal year ending March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
