<HEADLINE> Guangdong Customs Takes Steps to Promote Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Customs officials in south
China's Guangdong Province have worked out new ways to improve
services for foreign trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The major measures are:
</P>
<P>
--- Priority given to 70 large enterprises to develop
export-oriented economy;
</P>
<P>
--- On-the-spot services available to state-designated
high-tech and new technology development zones and exhibition
areas open mainly to foreigners;
</P>
<P>
--- Special services offered to high-tech and new technology
development zones, high-efficiency agricultural experimental
zones, science and technology poverty relief areas, modern
agricultural production bases and export-oriented agricultural
centers;
</P>
<P>
--- Unified handling time limit set for the passage of goods,
vehicles and personnel, as well as for recording and cancellation
of processing trade contracts, and registration of processing
businesses; and
</P>
<P>
--- On-the-spot handling of declaration formalities for small
amounts of imported parts and raw materials brought in by related
personnel and badly needed by large and medium-size state
enterprises, high-tech and new technology businesses, firms that
have a good reputation, and foreign-backed ventures.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is China's major exporter and importer. According to
statistics, Guangdong Customs handles 40 percent of the national
foreign trade volume annually, and another 40 percent of
processing trade contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
