<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Elected to WHO Executive Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has been elected an
executive committee member of the World Health Organization (WHO)
for a three-year term, the official Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There are 197 member countries in the WHO. It grants the voting
right to 30 countries once in three years on a rotational basis.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka was elected to the executive committee of the WHO
with effect from January 1998 for the three year term, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The WHO has also offered Sri Lanka 4.7 million U.S. dollars to
improve its health facilities, Health Minister Nimal Siripala de
Silva told the paper Monday.
</P>
<P>
As an executive committee member, Sri Lanka can obtain more
assistance from the WHO to improve both Western and Ayurveda
medicines, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to funds, Sri Lanka has been provided with other
assistance such as technology, equipment and training programs for
doctors, nurses and other staff abroad.
</P>
<P>
Under a WHO aided program, the Health Ministry hopes to send
some doctors, nurses and attendants for training courses at the
Varanasi University in India where both Ayurveda and Western
medicines have been synthesized to treat patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
