<HEADLINE> South China Province Makes Progress in Medical Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province has
reported remarkable progress in developing medical services,
resulting in an increased local average life expectancy from 35 to
72.8 years in the past more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province has established 2,595 medical
organizations with 32,450 medical workers; the province is taking
the leading position in terms of its number of medical workers per
1,000 people; the incidence of infectious diseases per 100,000
people has dropped from 247.24 in 1992 to 127.7 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Province has a high incidence of malaria, cholera,
dengue fever and filariasis due to its humid climate and heavy
rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The province has spent more than 100 million yuan annually to
build medical facilities since 1990.
</P>
<P>
A group of non-governmental hospitals has been established to
join the effort to promote overall development of the province's
medical services. 
</P>
