<HEADLINE> Panama Drivers Threaten to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Panama drivers are
threatening to strike unless the government agreed to amend
an agreement aimed at achieving cost-free, trans-border freight
transport with all Central American countries.
</P>
<P>
At present, agreement reciprocity applies only between Panama
and El Salvador, although other Central American countries were
expected to join.
</P>
<P>
Drivers complain that runs to other countries cost them heavily
in customs. border and transit charges.
</P>
<P>
They give as an example a trip from the Panama city of Chiriqui
to Nicaragua's Managua. It costs Panamanian drivers about 376
U.S. dollars, while their counterparts in other Central American
countries only pay three dollars to enter Panama.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Alvarado, General Secretary of the Drivers Labour Union
of Chiriqui demanded the agreement be reciprocal among all Central
American countries in order to cut the costs of Panama drivers.
</P>
<P>
Alvarado said drivers had trusted governor Ricardo Saval
because he said he had orders from President Ernesto Perez
Balladares to negotiate the negative points of the agreement with
other CentralAmerican countries.
</P>
<P>
If the agreement was not amended, the Panama drivers would stop
their trucks again to show the government their position.
</P>
<P>
The drivers barred Costa-Rican drivers from entering their
country in previous strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
