<HEADLINE> Chi Haotian, Vice-Chairman of Central Military Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Following is a biographical
sketch of Chi Haotian, who was reelected vice-chairman of the
Central Military Commission today at the First Session of the
Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Born in July, 1929; native of Zhaoyuan, Shandong Province;
joined army in July, 1945; joined Communist Party of China (CPC)
in October, 1946.
</P>
<P>
Chi started from a copy clerk, signalman and squad leader in
his teens, and rose to serve as company and battalion officers in
Third Field Army before founding of New China in 1949,
participating in a number of vital campaigns.
</P>
<P>
From 1950 to 1955, served as battalion instructor and director
of a regimental political department of Chinese People's
Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
From 1958 to 1960, studied at Infantry School of People's
Liberation Army (PLA) and Combination Department of PLA Military
College.
</P>
<P>
Served then as reginmental political department director,
regimental political commissar, division political department
director and division political commissar in 27th Corps in late
1960s and early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In 1970s, also served as leading official in Liberation Army
Daily, deputy editor-in-chief of People's Daily and deputy
political commissar of Beijing Military Area Command.
</P>
<P>
Between 1977 to 1992, Chi Haotian was deputy chief of General
Staff of PLA, political commissar of Jinan Military Area Command,
member of Central Military Commission and chief of General Staff
of PLA.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1995, served as member of Central Military
Commission, state councillor and minister of national defense.
</P>
<P>
Has been vice-chairman of Central Military Commission, state
councillor and minister of national defense since 1995.
</P>
<P>
He was member of 12th, 13th and 14th Central Committees of CPC,
and is member of Political Bureau of 15th CPC Central Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
