<HEADLINE> Myanmar Sets New Export Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has set a new target of
earning 200 million U.S. dollars from exports in 1998-99 fiscal
year beginning April, said official The New Light of Myanmar
newspaper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
New export items would be found to achieve the new target,
Myanmar Minister of Commerce Kyaw Than was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's traditional export commodities include rice, beans
and pulses, rubber, fish and prawn, teak and hardwood, base metal
and ores.
</P>
<P>
The new export target is obviously far lower than that in the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is now encouraging the private sector to boost
exports, Kyaw Than said.
</P>
<P>
An export promotion meeting was held by the ministry here
Monday, inviting new means and suggestions from local exporters
for the move.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar exported 725 million
dollars' worth of goods in the first ten months of 1997, up from
598 million dollars in the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's exports in the period, the private sector
contributed 75 percent or 548 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Myanmar's export and import volume dropped markedly
since the outbreak of the Asian financial turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
