<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Allows Government Employees to Enter Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province in east China has
issued a circular to encourage government employees to leave their
posts temporarily to work in privately or individually owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
The circular issued by the province's personnel department
stipulates that government workers can apply for a three-year
leave to work in private business. During their leave, they can
retain 60 percent of their salary and all of their subsidies.
</P>
<P>
When the leave is up, they have the right to return to their
former departments, or to compete in the open market.
</P>
<P>
Government employees are allowed to take early retirement or
resign to seek their opportunities in private businesses,
according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shubao, an official in the province's personnel
department, said this move is aimed at improving the private
sector and enabling government employees to find a larger arena
for their talents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
