<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Processing Trade Volume Going Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- China reported nearly 170
billion U.S. dollars worth of processing trade in 1997, up 15.75
percent over the previous year. Processing accounted for 52.2
percent of last year's foreign trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that processing trade has become the
largest contributor to the country's foreign trade, in contrast to
29.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1988 and 28.5 percent of the national
total imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
Major growth came from processing trade by overseas-funded
enterprises. In 1988, these businesses provided 14 percent of the
total processing trade, but in 1996 the percentage rose to 64.
</P>
<P>
Processing of some world name-brand products from Japan,
Europe, and the United States -- including electronics
information, stationery, shoes, and clothing -- has been moved to
China.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province in south China is a typical example. It
reported 93.85 billion U.S. dollars of processing trade last
year, making up 55.3 percent of the national total. However,
processing trade in the central and western parts is also on the
rise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
