<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asia Facing New Haze Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Barely a few months after haze
cleared away over Southeast Asia, the region is facing a new haze
threat from forest fires in Indonesia and Malaysia. Possibly, this
year's calamity in Southeast Asia will be even bigger than last
year's.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-January, official reports said, fires in Indonesia's
East Kalimantan and Sumatra have gutted over 65,000 hectares of
forest. In Miri, an oil town in Malaysia's Sarawak state, some 500
firefighters are curbing spreading fires covering some 1,000
hectares of forest.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of the new fires, a result of burning by some
companies for plantations, has made people in Southeast Asia
worrisome as memories of last year's nightmare are still fresh.
</P>
<P>
According to a February report by the World Wide Fund for
Nature, last year's haze caused by Indonesia's forest fire cost
the Southeast Asian region 1.384 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Falls in tourism, short-term health, industrial production and
fishing, cost Indonesia 1.012 billion dollars, Malaysia 310
million dollars and Singapore 62.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
But this year, the situation could be more serious because
Indonesia's fires are harder to stop and fires also occur in
Malaysia, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
At present, areas of Indonesia which should have enjoyed heavy
rainfall are experiencing a severe drought. With no rain expected
for months due to freak weather caused by El Nino, the fires are
likely to get worse, they said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, hit severely by the ongoing financial crisis, the
Indonesian government cannot allocate enough money to curb the
fires, they said.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to reduce economic losses and lessen
environmental damages to the region, environment ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) met in Malaysia at
the end of last month, and activated a haze action plan agreed on
last December.
</P>
<P>
Under the action plan, Indonesia focuses its action on fighting
the fires, Malaysia on preventing measures and Singapore on
satellite monitoring.
</P>
<P>
During the past two months, Indonesia and Malaysia have
dispatched aircraft to drop water-bombs and fire-retarding
chemicals on the disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
However, high-resolution satellite images show fires are still
spreading at an alarming rate. Early this month, forest fires in
Malaysia were reportedly limited to 200 hectares, but now are
covering 1,000 hectares. In East Kalimantan, dozens of new
outbreaks are spotted daily along the 80-kilometer highway between
Samarinda and Bontang, and hot spots increased to 394 last week.
</P>
<P>
A hot spot is a single pixel on satellite images depicting a
one square area, where one or more fires have been detected.
</P>
<P>
The new fires have caused serious damages to the environment in
disaster areas of the two countries. In Miri, the air pollution
index has breached the hazardous levels to 360, with visibility
down to 1.6 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
As Malaysia will host the Commonwealth Games in September,
officials fear that many athletes and visitors will stay away if
there is return to last year's smoke level.
</P>
<P>
For the moment, air pollution is limited to the disaster areas
of the two countries, but the situation may change soon. Experts
said that the northeast monsoon is blowing the smoke away from
Indonesia's northern neighbors, but everything will change when
the southwest monsoon begins in July.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists say that Southeast Asia must learn from the
terrible price it is paying for the forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Topfer, executive director of the United Nations
Environment Program, said that right now, the firefighting part is
the most important, but there must be a lot of effort put into
prevention.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, since the fires are now already in intensive
development, prevention may be not very successful this year, and
the world must come to Southeast Asia's assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
