<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Leftist Rebels Sign Human Rights Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government signed
late Monday night a human rights accord with the country's leftist
rebel group, the National Democratic Front (NDF), a breakthrough
that may finally lead to an end to a nearly three-decade-long
leftist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
The NDF peace panel led by Luis Jalandoni and the government
peace team lead by Howard Dee signed the Comprehensive Agreement
on Respect for Human Rights and International Humanitarian Law, in
The Hague, the Netherlands, the daily Philippine Star said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The accord was the first component of a proposed peace treaty
between the NDF and the government, which began peace negotiations
12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Details of the human rights agreement, which commits the two
sides to respect human rights, were not immediately released.
</P>
<P>
The government expected the signing of the accord to reduce
encounters between the military and the NDF's armed wing, the New
People's Army (NPA), in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The first fruit of this agreement must be a marked reduction
or, better yet, a total suspension of armed hostilities," the
government peace panel said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The leftist rebellion, which began in the late 1960s and peaked
during the mid-1980s, has claimed the lives of tens of thousands
of people in the country.
</P>
<P>
The NPA's strength shrank sharply to about 8,000 members from a
high of more than 26,000 in 1987 due to a series of massive
offensives launched by the military. Some NDF leaders fled to the
Netherlands in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The government and the NDF will begin to discuss political and
constitutional reforms in the next round of negotiations starting
this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
