<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile, Mexico Reject Helms-Burton Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Together, Chilean President
Eduardo Frei and his Mexican counterpart Ernesto Zedillo voiced
again their opposition against a U.S. law.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement Monday, the two presidents said they were
against the so-called Helms-Burton Act, as well as any law or
unilateral measure with an extra-territorial effect.
</P>
<P>
The law, initially designed to further the sanctions against
Cuba, "is against the regulations and principles of international
rights and ... the sovereignty of other countries," they said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Frei and Zedillo, here on visit since Sunday,
agreed that the U.S. application of certification processes in the
fight against drug trafficking is a big threat to multilateralism.
</P>
<P>
They expressed support for the initiative to organize a
Latin-American and the Caribbean Head of States summit currently
scheduled for the first half of 1999 in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The summit was expected to enhance economic exchange and
cooperation between Latin-America and the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The Chilean and Mexican leaders appreciated the work by the Rio
Group and backed the bloc's efforts to strengthen its mechanism as
the region's consultation and political reconciliation body.
</P>
<P>
They wanted to see the Rio Group playing a more active role as
as a speaker for Latin American and the Caribbean regions and for
other countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
