<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dongting Lake Winter Habitat for Endangered Species of Geese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- Dongting Lake in central China's
Hunan Province has become the winter habitat for white-forehead
wild geese, one of the world's endangered species.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates by Chinese and Japanese experts engaged
in bird protection, there are 14,000 wild geese in the nature
reserve of the Dongting Lake, the second largest of its kind in
China.
</P>
<P>
The white-forehead goose only weighs 1.3-to-2 kilograms. There
are only 20,000 in the world, said experts attending a seminar on
bird protection around the Dongting Lake.
</P>
<P>
Occupying about 15,000 square kilometers, Dongting Lake is home
to more than 16 million migrant birds in winter.
</P>
<P>
The eastern section of the lake is a state-class nature reserve
and has been included on the International Important Wetland List.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the white-forehead wild geese leave the lake
in late March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Liver Human Transplant in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A 21-year-old woman received a
new liver at a hospital here Monday and became the first patient
to undergo such an organ transplant in Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The woman, who suffered terminal liver failure, was in the
operation room for 11 hours at the Instituto Nacional de
Enfermedades Hepaticas of the army's central hospital.
</P>
<P>
The liver was from a 44-year-old man who died the same day. His
other organs would be distributed among several receptors in the
coming days, said the National Bank of Organs and Tissues.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Edgardo Tortorel, the head of a medical team in the liver
transplant, said the procedure on the woman was successful so far.
</P>
<P>
In the past, as Uruguayan physicians were yet to develop the
skills needed, patients had to travel to Argentina to undergo
liver transplant under an agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With the success on the first case, Uruguayans could receive
such surgery in their own country, physicians said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
