<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile, Mexico to Forge Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Chile and Mexico committed
themselves, by signing a joint statement Monday, to forge closer
ties for bilateral cooperation in various areas.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed here at the "Palacio de Moneda" by
Chilean Presidents Eduardo Frei and his Mexican counterpart
Ernesto Zedillo, who had been in Chile since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
While promising more cooperation in areas like politics,
technology and culture, the two presidents were also looking
forward toward the signing of a free trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral free trade instrument would replace a trade
cooperation document that has been in practice between Chile and
Mexico, both economic giants in Latin America, since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The new document, likely to create additional jobs for both
countries, was expected at a hemispheric summit bringing together
leaders of both North and South American countries later this year.
</P>
<P>
Also there at the summit, the second of the kind, leaders will
start negotiations for kicking off a hemispheric free trade regime.
</P>
<P>
Frei and Zedillo, whose stay here at the invitation of his host
would last through Wednesday, said they would focus cooperative
projects on areas helpful for the development of both countries.
</P>
<P>
They also outlined the need to continue to work on the
Chilean-Mexican integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
