<HEADLINE> Latin American Brief Economical News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are brief
economic news items from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA -- Two Colombian, two Argentinian and two
Brazilian banks headed the list of the best Latin-American Bank
entities, according to the magazine "America Economia".
</P>
<P>
The Argentinian Bank Rio de la Plata had the best grade,
followed by Bradesco from Brazil, Industrial Banks from Colombia,
Iatu from Brazil and the French Bank from Argentina.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
CITY OF PANAMA -- The imports of the free trade zone of Colon
in Panama rose to 391.6 million U.S. dollars in February and 481.8
million U.S. dollars for re-exports.
</P>
<P>
Imports increased by 3.2 percent and re-exports 9.5 percent
compared with the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
CARACAS - Imports in Venezuela reached 12.1 billion dollars in
1997, an increase of 35.9 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The electric sector was the main buyer, followed by the
transportation, chemical products, metals, agriculture, food
industry, beverages, tobacco and paper sectors.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the imports come from the United States, 6.3
percent from Colombia, 4.9 percent from Brazil and 4.3 percent
from Mexico and Italy respectively.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO - Exports of Uruguayan beef and mutton products
reached 81.9 million dollars from January to the first week of
March, an increase of 13.5 percent over the same period of 1997.
(to be continued)
nnnn
</P>
