<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Adopts Stricter Rules on Entry of New Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has imposed stricter bank entry qualifications and
competency criteria for bank ownership effective this month,
Manila Bulletin reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes was quoted as saying
the stricter requirements form part of the central bank's move to
further strengthen the banking system and make it less vulnerable
to shocks.
</P>
<P>
The new guidelines include the presentation of evidence of
assets ownership of the investors, net worth of at least twice the
amount of the proposed investment in a bank and presentation of
sufficient proof of resources of income to support net worth.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the monetary authorities want the proposed
bank president has at least two years' experience as a senior
official of a bank or non-bank financial institution.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said the move aims to
better ensure that potential main bank investors have adequate
legitimate resources to fully support their prospective bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
