<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Irrigation Project Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 17 (Xinhua) -- The 2,254-year-old Dujiangyan
irrigation project, the oldest of its kind in the world, is
playing a greater role in securing agricultural harvests for
related areas.
</P>
<P>
The March 2 operation of a new water distribution system in the
Dujiangyan irrigated area of southwest China's Sichuan Province
was considered one of the most advanced irrigation projects in the
country.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 officials and technicians were involved in the
working the system and held accountable for its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The project now covers an irrigated area of 670,000 hectares in
34 counties, three times that before New China was founded in
1949, to become the country's largest gravity irrigation area.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the area reported an all-time high grain output of
approximately 6 billion kilograms despite a serious drought in the
last 60 years, contributing greatly to the province's harvest as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the project stored more than a billion
cubic meters of water. During last winter and this spring, the
Dujiangyan Administration spent 66.24 million yuan completing 1.78
million cubic meters of earth and stone to get ready for
large-scale water supplies after April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
