<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Ticketless Fans to Stay Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's sports minister urged
thousands of ticketless soccer fans on Monday to stay away from
the World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
"If you haven't got a ticket for the World Cup finals, do not
travel," Banks told the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
Banks said the government backed the Football Association in
its efforts to secure more tickets for its 32,000 registered fans.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of dissatisfaction with the allocation, I would
very much like to be able to wish up more tickets but
unfortunately I can't do so."
</P>
<P>
England supporters have been allocated 3,790 tickets for their
first game against Tunisia, 2,749 for their match against Romania
and 2,589 when they play Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Banks reminded English fans, who still have a bad reputation
for hooliganism in Europe, that they were ambassadors for their
country and misbehaviour could handicap England's bid for the 2006
finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
