<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, March 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States confirmed Monday that it will
not sponsor a censure on China's human rights record in view of
the changes in that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The State Department Spokesman James Rubin said at a press
briefing that "We took this decision because of the steps taken
and the anticipation of further progress." Press reports said that
the U.S. decided to give up the attempt to sponsor a resolution
condemning China on human rights issue just before the United
Nation's Human Rights Commission meets in Geneva this week.
(US-China Resolution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States would not consider to withdraw
any of the 37,000 American troops from South Korea as part of the
peace negotiations with the Democratic Poeple's Republic of Korea
(DPRK), the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
DPRK officials have said during the run-up to the four-party
talks, now formally opened in Geneva on Monday, that the
withdrawal of U.S. forces remained a key demand in the peace
talks. (US-DPRK-Troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Development Programme
(UNDP) and the Government of Cuba have launched a new program to
implement a range of macro-economic reforms in such areas as
budget planning, social security and banking, a release from UNDP
said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The release said staff training will be provided for managers
in several key state institutions, including the central bank and
the Ministry of Economy and Planning. The UNDP is providing 1.15
million U.S. dollars in funds and Norway will provide 300,000
U.S. dollars. Brazil, Mexico and Chile will send economic experts
to Cuba. (UNDP-Cuba-Economic Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Monday refused to take any
suggestions that Washington should have a dialogue with Iraq as a
way to clarify U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe it would be wise to have a dialogue with
Iraq," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters. He
was answering a reporter's question of what the United States
would react if King Hussein of Jordan raises the suggestion for a
possible dialogue when he visits Washington, probably this week.
(US-Iraq-Dialogue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Yugoslavia believes that Russia can play a very
important role in settling the Kosovo crisis, the Interfax news
agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Ambassador in Moscow Danilo
Markovic, commenting on the coming trip by Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to several former Yugoslav republics,
said that Russia has supported and is continuing to provide
support for the territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Markovic expressed regret that the Contact Group on
former Yugoslavia in its statement on the situation with Kosovo
approved in London last week did not set a clear line separating
"terrorist activity from legal actions by law enforcement agencies
within the bounds of struggle against terrorism."
(Russia-Yugoslavia-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
