<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federation to Appeal Against Martinez Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish athletics body said
here on Monday that they would be appealing against the withdrawl
of two-year doping ban on discus thrower David Martinez by a
sports discipline body.
</P>
<P>
Martinez, holder of Spain's discus record, tested positive for
the steroid nandrolene at a meeting in Halle, Germany, last May.
</P>
<P>
He was suspended but appealed to the country's sports
discipline council (CEDD) claiming that he had eaten infected pig
meat.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the CEDD said the doping test laboratory in Cologne
could have made a mistake and there was not sufficient evidence
Martinez had taken the drug.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish Athletics Federation spokesperson said the decision
put the body in a difficult position.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson said the CEDD is this country's supreme body
for sports discipline but meanwhile his organization is a member
of the International Amateur Athletic Federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
