<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lombardi Wins Sixth Cycling Stage in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Giovanni Lombardi overpaced Fabian
Jeker to take the sixth stage of the Tirreno-Adriatico cycling
race on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rolf Jaermann assumed the overall lead but world road race
champion Laurent Brochard quit after being injured in a collision.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Lombardi and Switzerland's Jeker broke away from the
field for a two-man sprint in the closing stretch of the 224
kilometers from Teramo to Frontone along Italy's eastern coast.
</P>
<P>
Jaermann, also Swiss, moved up from second in the overall
standings as Denmark's Rolf Sorensen tumbled from the top by
finishing the stage 10 minutes behind the leaders.
</P>
<P>
Brochard, fifth overall before the stage, needed stitches for a
thigh injury and would miss Saturday's Milan-to-San Remo classic,
which opens the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Tour de France champion Jan Ullrich and 1997 World Cup titlist
Michele Bartoli dropped out of the Tirreno-Adriatico last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
