<HEADLINE> U.S. Says No American Troops Will Withdraw from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States would not
consider to withdraw any of the 37,000 American troops from
South Korea as part of the peace negotiations with the
Democratic Poeple's Republic of Korea (DPRK), the State
Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
DPRK officials have said during the run-up to the four-party
talks, now formally opened in Geneva on Monday, that the
withdrawal of U.S. forces remained a key demand in the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"That's obviously a non-starter," State Department spokesman
James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea wanted the issue of
the withdrawal of U.S. troops to be on a formal agenda item
during the four-party talks, but the United States refused.
</P>
<P>
DPRK officials finally agreed to begin the four-party
discussion after the United States said they were free to raise
the question of troop withdrawal.  
</P>
