<HEADLINE> U.S. Doubts Cook's Har Homa Trip would Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that Washington does not believe Britain's Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook could help ease Middle East tensions by
visiting a controversial Jewish settlement project.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said Cook would visit the settlement, known as Har
Homa in Hebrew and Jabal Abu Ghneim in Arabic, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the Jewish settlement was decided by the
Israeli government last March, which was met with protests from
the Palestinians and from the Arab states, and was greeted with
criticism from the international community as the decision was
sheer betrayal by Israel of Oslo peace accords agreed upon by both
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has since been brought to a
standstill because of Israel's violation of the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Cook's plan to visit the Jewish settlement in the east part of
Jerusalem was first met with opposition from Israel which
threatened to exclude the European Union from Middle East
peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
But Israel later agreed Cook's visit plan on the condition that
he would be accompanied by Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin, in answering a
question whether Cook's visit would "help settle things down" in
the region, said: "It doesn't look that way."
</P>
<P>
But he said it was up to Cook to decide where he wanted to go.
</P>
<P>
A senior U.S. official said that Washington had told Cook what
the result would be for his decision to visit the settlement.
</P>
<P>
"It would be controversial, and that has proven to be true," he
said. "It's a shame that it's overshadowing the other parts of
(Cook's) trip."
</P>
<P>
Rubin reiterated that the United States was again looking at
ways to move forward, but had made no decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
