<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Criticizes Employers on Worker Consultation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, Monday criticized a European
employers' group for refusing to negotiate rules with its union
counterpart on worker consultation.
</P>
<P>
The Union of Industrial and Employer Confederations of Europe
(UNICE) said Monday that it had decided against talks with the
European Trade Union Confederation (ETUC) and public employers'
group CEEP to set out rules which could then become EU law.
</P>
<P>
"This is a serious setback for social dialogue," Commission
President Jacques Santer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive asked UNICE last year to negotiate new rules,
which would require companies to set up procedures for informing
and consulting their workers at national levels about major
decisions.
</P>
<P>
"Our member federations are virtually unanimous in their
conviction the European Union should not intervene in such a
matter, which has no transnational implications," UNICE President
Francois Perigot said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
An EU directive already requires big multinational companies to
set up European works councils or other consultation systems.
</P>
<P>
Under procedures introduced by the EU's 1992 Maastricht treaty,
EU ministers could agree to turn an agreement negotiated by the
employers' and workers' bodies into EU law.
</P>
<P>
Social Affairs Commissioner Padraig Flynn said that in the
absence of negotiations he would propose EU legislation on the
issue. The Commission also called for "mini-summit" with employer
and trade union groups to discuss future relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
