<HEADLINE> British FM Determined to Visit Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here on Monday that he is determined to visit Har Homa
in Arab East Jerusalem despite Israel's opposition.
</P>
<P>
"I will go to Har Homa to see the situation for myself," Cook
told reporters when he arrived here in the afternoon for a one-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
He will have "no objection," if Israeli officials accompany him
to Har Homa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has warned that Cook's planned visit to Har Homa would
harm the role of the European Union (EU) in mediating the peace
process. Britain is holding the rotating presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Israel broke ground for the construction of a Jewish settlement
on Har Homa a year ago, which brought the peace talks between the
Palestinians and the Israelis to a grind halt.
</P>
<P>
Cook was critical of Israel's policy of expanding settlements
in the occupied Arab lands. "It is wrong to expand settlements on
the occupied territories, (because) it does not fit in with the
spirit of the Oslo accords," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook called on Israel to refrain from settlement expansion in
Arab East Jerusalem, which he said would help build trust between
itself and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who arrived here after ending a brief visit to Egypt, is
on the second leg of his Middle East tour, which will also take
him to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The EU has proposed that Israel freeze construction of Jewish
settlements, implement significant troop pullback in the West
Bank, and the Palestinians fulfill its commitments to meet
Israel's security demands.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal has reportedly been snubbed by the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
