<HEADLINE> Clinton Opposes Limiting NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
pressed the Senate to resist limits on expanding the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) after Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
In letters over the weekend to Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi and Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, Clinton criticized proposals that would impose a
moratorium on additional NATO members after the three.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly urge the Senate to reject any effort to mandate a
pause on the process of enlargement," Clinton said in the letter
which was issued Monday by the White House.
</P>
<P>
"Such a mandate is unnecessary and unwise, for it would reduce
our own country's flexibility and leverage, fracture NATO's open
door consensus, and draw a new and potentially destabilizing
dividing line in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must leave the door open to the addition of other qualified
new members in the future," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton said that neither his administration, nor
U.S. NATO allies, "has made any decisions or commitments about
when the next invitations for membership should be extended, or to
whom."
</P>
<P>
The accords to accept the three new members have got a
bipartisan support in the Senate and analysts believe that they
will be approved.
</P>
<P>
However, a group of senators led by John Warner, R-Va., and
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., are seeking a three-year freeze
on further NATO members.
</P>
<P>
They have also asked Lott to delay action on the overall
measure, at least until after Congress' April recess.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Monday, Lott said he still hoped to
get to the NATO bill later this week, but that it might be
postponed until next week because of other matters before the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
"The president has indicated that he would hope that we could
do it sometime this week, because he's going to be out of town
next week," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton plans a week-long trip to Africa next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
