<HEADLINE> U.S. Refuses Suggestion of Dialogue with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Monday
refused to take any suggestions that Washington should have a
dialogue with Iraq as a way to clarify U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe it would be wise to have a dialogue with
Iraq," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He was answering a reporter's question of what the United
States would react if King Hussein of Jordan raises the
suggestion for a possible dialogue when he visits Washington,
probably this week.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have much to say to Iraq, and until they do what
the international community has demanded for so long, this isn't
a question where there's a confused message that needs to be
clarified with direct discussions," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Reports on Sunday said top Iraqi officials expressed their
wishes to hold direct dialogue with the United States and
Britain so as to establish a kind of "normal relations."
</P>
<P>
But Rubin made an immediate response that Washington would
not change its policy toward Iraq and said what Baghdad should
do was to fully comply with U.N. resolutions on weapons
inspections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
