<HEADLINE> Report: Congressional Candidates Raise Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Fund-raising figures for 1997
by the Federal Election Commission of the United States show that
congressional candidates set new records.
</P>
<P>
The total raised by congressional candidates last year was 233
million dollars, up 26 percent from 1995, the previous
non-election year, The Washington Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Senate receipt were up 44 percent to 97 million dollars, while
fund-raising for the House of Representatives races also set a
record, up 16 percent to 136 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four Senate candidates and seven House candidates
entered the year 1998, which will see mid-term election in
November, with more than one million dollars in the till included
five Democratic incumbents and two Republicans.
</P>
<P>
The House challenger with the most cash on hand, New Jersey
Democrat Carl Mayer, had 506,000 dollars, the Post said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
