<HEADLINE> EU Farm Ministers Vote to Ease Ban on British Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Agriculture ministers from the
15 European Union (EU) member countries Monday voted to ease a ban
on British beef exports which was imposed two years ago over mad
cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The farm ministers voted to show their support for a proposal
allowing some beef to be shipped from Northern Ireland, where
computer records can show cattle to be free of brain-wasting mad
cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The vote, which offered a ray of hope to all Britain's cattle
farmers, was "the first step in the resumption of trade in beef
between the U.K. and the rest of the world," Britain's junior farm
minister Lord Donoughue told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
British Farm Minister Jack Cunningham said this was "excellent
news" for all Britain's cattle farmers who have been crippled by
the two-year-old trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
"The decision recognizes that our beef is safe to export," said
the British farm minister, adding that the vote had demonstrated
that the approach of the British government was getting results.
</P>
<P>
Only two EU farm ministers -- Germany and Belgium -- Monday
voted against the plan. Luxembourg and Spain abstained from the
vote.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal by the farm ministers, a final inspection
visit to Northern Ireland will be carried out by EU food safety
experts before the final decision is taken to ease the ban.
</P>
<P>
Germany and Belgium said they wanted another ministerial
meeting after the inspection visit to decide on whether the ban
should be eased.
</P>
<P>
Phelim O'Neill, marketing manager of the Livestock and Meat
Commission for Northern Ireland, said he expected exports could
resume within six to eight weeks, but acknowledged that was just
the start of the battle to regain lost market share.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be trying to win back an export market worth an
estimated 180 million pounds (300 million U.S. dollars) before the
ban was in place," he said. "But we now also have to battle
against a strong pound."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
