<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Urges Milosevic to Talk With Kosovo Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The involvement of Slobodan
Milosevic, president of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, is
important to negotiating a resolution of the Kosovo crisis, a
senior diplomat in Bonn said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The central point is whether Belgrade is prepared to open a
(serious) dialogue with the Kosovo Albanians," the government
source said on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot expect the Albanians to sit at a table with the
Serbians while the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia says it has
nothing to do with it," said the source.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations need to be between Yugoslav President Milosevic
and the Albanians, said the diplomat.
</P>
<P>
So far Belgrade has dispatched Serbia's deputy premier, Ratko
Markovic, as the representative for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Kosovo Albanians Monday for the third time
boycotted talks with Belgrade originally scheduled in the Kosovo
district capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
They said they would not enter into conditional talks with
Serbian officials or allow them to force a `constitutional
framework" on the region that abolished its autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Markovic said the ethnic Albanians attempted an unrealistic
goal of the secession of Kosovo (from Serbia), which could not be
achieved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The senior diplomat in Bonn said the Kosovo Albanians were
right to boycott negotiations and demand a better framework for
talks on the future of Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
