<HEADLINE> Russia Suffers from Trade Discrimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia loses about 1.7 billion
U.S. dollars annually because of the trade discrimination, Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a session of the Consultative Council for Foreign
Investments, Chernomyrdin said that this year the Russian
government will start intensive talks on admission to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
He noted Russia must carefully verify the tariff tactics
coordinate its moves with partners in the Customs Union. The
Russian government had sent an official application for membership
to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin noted that Russia's admission to the organization
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Council "may considerably facilitate
the inflow of foreign capital to Russia's Far East and
Trans-Baikal region."
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet is drafting a national plan for the liberalization
of trade and investments, which Russia will offer its partners in
this international organization, Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
The volume of foreign investment in the country's economy
amounted to about 10 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, including 4
billion U.S. dollars in direct investments, a report cited
Chernomyrdin as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
