<HEADLINE> Pakistani National Economy Improved: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Monday there have been improvement in the country's
economy despite recent economic turmoil in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a joint meeting of central working committee
and parliamentary parties in the Senate and National Assembly of
Pakistan Muslim League (Nawaz).
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign exchange reserves have increased, stock
market has gained stability and prices are under control.
</P>
<P>
There has been improvement in balance of payments position and
trade gap would be around 2.5 billion U.S. dollars this year as
against 4 billion dollars last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
This was possible due to increase in exports, decrease in
imports as well as additional remittances of 300 million dollars,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the inflation rate will be around 8.8 percent this
year as compared to between 12 to 13 percent in the last financial
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said that industrial recovery, which was
targeted as 7 percent, will be between 4 to 5 percent. And there
has been significant improvement in the agricultural sector with
bumper rice and sugarcane production, he added. 
</P>
