<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBCA Downgrades Indonesia's Long-Term Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Fitch IBCA, the international
rating agency, downgraded the long-term foreign currency rating of
Indonesia to B- Monday.
</P>
<P>
The short-term foreign currency rating is maintained at B but
the long-term local currency rating is downgraded to BB+ from
BBB-.
</P>
<P>
These ratings apply to public and publicly guaranteed senior,
unsecured debt and set a ceiling for all other Indonesian
entities, according to IBCA.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating economic and financial situation since last
summer has raised grave concerns among financial institutes all
over the world about Indonesia's capacity to service its external
debt.
</P>
<P>
At current exchange rates, much of its corporate sector is
technically bankrupt and an unofficial debt moratorium is already
in place.
</P>
<P>
IBCA said sovereign default, however unintentional, could also
become a real possibility unless Indonesia reaches an agreement
with the IMF very soon and is seen to deliver on its commitments.
</P>
<P>
The agency commented that it is essential that any modification
to Indonesia's program, agreed by the IMF, offers a credible way
forward to restore the economy to sustainable health, and not just
a quick fix. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
