<HEADLINE> Sonia Gandhi Offers Constructive Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Sonia Gandhi, who took total
command of the Congress on Monday, offered "constructive
cooperation" to a new government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party
(BJP), the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general body meeting of the Congress
Parliamentary Party (CPP) after her election as its chairperson,
Sonia Gandhi said her party would offer constructive cooperation
to the new government for those policies which were in the
interests of the country.
</P>
<P>
Sonia Gandhi, Congress star campaigner in the just-concluded
general elections to the 12th Lower House of the Parliament,
succeeded Sitaram Kesri to become the new president of the
Congress party last Saturday at a meeting of the Congress Working
Committee, the highest decision-making body of the party.
</P>
<P>
Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan appointed BJP leader
Atal Behari Vajpayee on Sunday to form a new government and
Vajpayee will be sworn in as Prime Minister on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sonia Gandhi, whose Italian origin gave her opponents
propaganda grist, gave no indication of the Congress' stand on the
crucial confidence vote in Lok Sabha sought by Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
She said that she would measure up to the responsibility which
the Congress has imposed on her.
</P>
<P>
Appealing to the party members to strengthen their resolve to
combat communalism and sectarianism, she admitted that the
Congress did not have the privilege to provide leadership in
government formation after the recent elections.
</P>
<P>
The Italian-born chairperson constituted a six-member committee
to coordinate with other secular forces both within and outside
the parliament to devise strategies to challenge the BJP-led
government.
</P>
<P>
The dual chief of the century-old Congress is neither a member
of Lok Sabha, the House of the People, nor a member of Rajya
Sabha, the Council of states.
</P>
<P>
The 52-year-old widow of assassinated former prime minister
Rajiv Gandhi was born into a family of modest means in an obscure
village on the banks of river Po neat Turin, northwest of Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
