<HEADLINE> IDB Attaches Importance to Social Programs in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- More than half the lending
program of the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) during 1997
was dedicated to social sector investment, poverty reduction and
modernization of the state, the IDB reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to its 1997 annual report released Monday, the IDB's
6 billion U.S. dollar lending program made the bank the main
source of development finance for the region for the fourth
consecutive year, particularly for the smaller countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The IDB's disbursements reached a record high of 5.4 billion
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank also approved 77 million dollars in grants for 318
technical cooperation projects in 1997, investing in such areas as
project preparation, sector studies, institutional strengthening,
human resources and regional integration.
</P>
<P>
In the social area, the IDB approved 47 projects totaling some
2.6 billion dollars, or 43 percent of the value of the lending
program, for investments in education, health, water and
sanitation, social investment funds and reforms, urban development
and housing as well as environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
According to the 200-page report, loan approvals for direct
financing to the private sector for infrastructure projects
reached a record 320 million dollars as against 198 million
dollars a year earlier. Approval for syndicated loans reached 563
million dollars, an increase of 136 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Latin America and the Caribbean grew 5.2 percent in 1997, the
second most rapid rate of growth since 1980, and inflation
continued its steady decline of recent years. The median inflation
rate for the region last year was less than 9 percent, compared
with 11 percent in 1996, which capital flows reached a record 70
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
