<HEADLINE> Water Week Begins in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The annual Water Week
began on Monday in Pretoria in a bid to ensure all people in the
country to have access to clean water.
</P>
<P>
South African Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal, who
inaugurated the event, said that the government has been doing
its utmost to speed up water projects in the country so that all
South Africans could have proper access to water in the early
years of the new century.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, over two million more people enjoyed
water supply, and the pace was being quickened.
</P>
<P>
The Water Week will be highlighted by various special
activities throughout the country, which include President Nelson
Mandela's participation at the opening of a water project in
KwaZulu Natal Province.
</P>
<P>
The theme of these activities is that all South Africans
should work together to conserve water, said Water Chief
Executive Vincent Bath.
</P>
<P>
He warned that "unless we begin using our water more
efficiently, we will run out of natural water suplies by the year
2020."
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been classified as a water-stressed country
in terms of international standards, he said. This situation
would not be changed by just two or three seasons of good rains.
</P>
<P>
Asmal also said that water conservation was vital, and much
progress had been made to change the thinking of South Africans
in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"The community water supply and sanitation program is one of
the challenges by which we shall be judged by future
generations," said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
