<HEADLINE> Le Monde Plays Down Gains by Left Parties in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The French daily Le Monde Monday
played down the gains won by the leftist parties in the regional
elections Sunday, and highlighted the scores held out by the
far-right National Front and the newly erupting extreme-left
groups such as Lutte Ouvriere.
</P>
<P>
"The pluralist left has not really confirmed... its victory of
legislative elections of 1997," said Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
It estimated that the leftwing parties have only won 36.48
percent of the votes in France proper, 5.77 points lower than what
it won in the legislative elections and slightly higher than 35.85
percent won by the right wing opposition Rally for the Republic
(RPR) and Union for French Democracy (UDF).
</P>
<P>
The Socialist-led leftwing parties will have absolute majority
in the regional parliament of Limoussin in the mountainous Massive
Central, and relative majority in nine other regions, while the
RPR and UDF will have absolute majority in the local parliament of
Pays de la Loire, a castle-dotted region extending from the Loire
Valley, and six other regions, according to Le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The extreme-left groups, such as a previously unknown party
called Lutte Ouvriere (Workers' Fight), won 4.38 percent of the
votes -- mostly coming from those who voted for the Socialists and
Communists in 1997 -- and will enter some regional councils or
parliaments for the first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
