<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Leaders on Unilateral Pullout From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli leaders reiterated
Israel's readiness to carry out immediately a unilateral
withdrawal from South Lebanon provided that Lebanon assumes its
security responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a ceremony to inaugurate a police
station in Jerusalem, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Israel is ready to pull out from Lebanon immediately according
to United Nations resolution 425, if Lebanese government fulfills
its international obligations on preventing terror attacks against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Israeli government would conduct orderly
discussions on Lebanese issue in the coming days. He said the
425 resolution also required Lebanon to take its international
obligations of maintaining peace and stability in South Lebanon
after an Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, Netanyahu demanded Lebanese government dismantle
the anti-Israeli guerrilla forces Hezbollah (Party of God) and
promise not to harm Israeli allies in the region, especially
the pro-Israeli South Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting of Knesset (Parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
also said that Israel would try to reach an agreement with
Lebanon on the withdrawal. He stressed that Israeli troops are
happy to leave the region if Lebanese government exercises
authority to safeguard the safety of Israeli northern border.
</P>
<P>
The committee also discussed a withdrawal proposal put forward
by National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon who launched the
aggression against Lebanon in 1982 when he was the defense
minister. The military action led to the establishment of
so-called South Lebanon Security Zone in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Sharon proposed a phased unilateral pullout from South
Lebanon, which contains a stern warning against the failure by
Lebanese government in preventing guerrilla attacks against
Israel's north.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Uzi Landau came out in support for Sharon's
proposal, saying this formula would not allow Syria to benefit
from the pullout.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise in the guerrilla war in South Lebanon and
a desire to deviate attention on the stalled Israeli-Palestinian
peace talks prompted the latest Israeli diplomatic offensive on
Lebanese pullout.
</P>
<P>
But analysts remain doubtful if the Israeli initiative has
even a moderate chance of success given the opposition of
Syria, which is believed to use the Lebanese issue as a
bargaining chip to retrieve the Golan Heights occupied by
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Stresses Political Aspect of Hajj Ritual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 16 (Xinhua) - Iran Monday stressed the political
aspect of the Muslim hajj rituals as Iranian pilgrims started to
leave for the annual hajj performance in Mecca of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
"There is no distinction between the political dimension of
the hajj rituals and those pertaining to worship, Mohammadi
Reyshahri, representative of Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei said at a special ceremony at Tehran international
airport when seeing off the first group of Iranian pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iranian pilgrims are messengers of unity and
amity and those sowing discord among Muslims should know that
they have no place among the Muslims who would foil their
conspiracies, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not mention whether the Iranian pilgrims
would stage anti-U.S. political demonstrations again during the
hajj rituals in Mecca. The demonstrations during the past few
years seriously harmed relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran-Riyadh relations warmed up only after the election
of Iranian President Mohammad Khatami who advocated friendly
and peaceful coexistence with regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Before the first group of Iranian pilgrims left Iran,
President Khatami sent his Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi to
Saudi Arabia, handing over a letter to the Saudi Crown
Prince Amir Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Although the content of the letter was not revealed,
observers believed that Khatami expected a coordination from the
Saudi side with Iran over hajj issue in order to keep
bilateral relations moving forward.
</P>
<P>
"We hope effective steps will be taken to restore the rights
of the Muslims thanks to the insight and the wisdom of the Saudi
statesmen," Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance Ataollah
Mohajerani also said at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that some 87,000 Iranian pilgrims would
attend the hajj rituals in Mecca this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
