<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Says "Anxious" to Visit Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said on Monday that he wanted to see for himself the
situation in Har Homa in traditionally Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Cook made the remark when talking with British reporters who
accompanied him on his flight from Cyprus to Cairo, where he was
to pay a four-hour visit at the start of his Middle East trip.
</P>
<P>
The British top diplomat's planned visit to Har Homa, where
Israel is expanding Jewish settlement despite world outcry, has
arisen controversy in Israel, which went out its way to prevent
the trip.
</P>
<P>
Cook, however, defended his decision. "I am anxious to see Har
Homa for myself. I would have thought that it would be in the
interests of both parties including the government of Israel that
were informed of seeing the situation myself," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's construction of Jewish buildings at Har Homa in March
1997 sent the Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations into a
impasse, which has so far remained unbroken.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Har Homa trip was part of his visit to the
Palestinian National Authority, Cook said he would view the site
"from land which is under the Palestinian control," stopping short
of saying he would set foot on the soil there.
</P>
<P>
Israel on Monday threatened to deny the European Union (EU) as
a mediator in the peace process if Cook insists on going
there. Britain now holds the rotating presidency of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cook told reporters that Britain and the EU opposed the Israeli
practice of settlement expansion, a stance he claimed is shared by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I do want to take this opportunity to say quite clearly that
our approach has been impartial and that we do want to make
progress on the peace process with both parties," said Cook.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Cairo, Cook, together with EU Mideast peace
envoy Miguel Moratinos, held an hour-long meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on ways to
revive the peace process, provide economic assistance to Iraqi
people and solve the Libya-West crisis over Lockerbie incident.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Cook said the European Union (EU) would
continue to support the Middle East peace process and the
Palestinians as it has done in the past.
</P>
<P>
Cook would hold further talks with his Egyptian counterpart on
bilateral ties and an EU proposal aimed at pushing forward the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for Palestinian commitment to Israel's
security demands, and urges Israel to implement a significant
troop redeployment in the West Bank, halt settlement expansion and
support Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
Cook was leaving here later in the afternoon for Jordan to
continue Mideast trip, which also includes Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He had been scheduled to arrive here Sunday night, but was
forced to stop over in Cyprus due to a sandstorm that hit Egypt,
Lebanon, Cyprus and other regional states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
