<HEADLINE> Greek Drachma Devalues, Cyprus Little Affected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The devaluation of the Greek
currency drachma will have only marginal repercussions on Cypriot
economy, the Central Bank of Cyprus said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in a press release that these
repercussions would be direct and indirect and relate to bilateral
trade, tourism and exports to third countries.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government recently devalued the drachma by 14
percent when the currency entered the European Exchange Rate
Mechanism in preparation for a unified European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said Greek exports to Cyprus will be more
competitive while Cypriot goods exported to Greece will be less
competitive after the depreciation of drachma.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade transactions between Cyprus and Greece is
too small, reaching only 7.5 percent, compared with the total
trade transactions between Cyprus and overseas markets, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism will be directly affected, however, since Greek
tourists will have to pay more for their holidays in Cyprus while
Cypriots will benefit from their visits in Greece.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the number of Greek tourists visiting the
Mediterranean island is small and any fluctuation will not affect
the total number of tourists to Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
