<HEADLINE> Cypriot National Guard Chief to Be Replaced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus announced on Monday that
its National Guard (armed forces) Commander, Greek Lieutenant
General Nicolaos Vorvolakos will be replaced by his compatriot
Major General Demetrios Demou.
</P>
<P>
The procedure for the replacement is underway, and the time
when Demou takes over the post will be decided by Cypriot Defense
Minister Yiannakis Omirou and his Greek counterpart Akis
Tsohatzopoulos at a meeting in Athens later this month, Cypriot
government spokesman Chirstos Stylianides told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between the two countries, many senior posts
of the Cypriot National Guard are taken by Greek officers.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the defense ministers of the two neighbors
would also discuss the inauguration of an air base near the
southwest coast, which is seen by Turkey and Turkish Cypriots as a
threat.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements for the ceremony will be decided after evaluating
Cyprus' strategic plans with regard to the peace process of the
island and the accession talks with the European Union due to
start on March 31, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The air base near the western coastal town of Paphos was
constructed last January under a joint defense pact signed between
Cyprus and Greece in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, however, has warned that
if Greek military aircraft take off from the air base, their wings
"will be broken" by Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by Greek Cypriot supporters of a union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1984 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, against
the internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus dominated by the
Greek Cypriots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
