<HEADLINE> Mozambican Local Elections Postponed to June 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Council of Ministers of
Mozambique decided at an extraordinary meeting Monday that June
30 be the country's local elections day.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time for the local elections to be
postponed. The local elections were originally scheduled to be
held in 33 cities and towns at the end of last December, then
were postponed to the first quarter of this year and last time
postponed to May 29.
</P>
<P>
The latest postponement proposal was presented to the Council
of Ministers by the National Commission of Elections last Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release by the National Commission of
Elections, the proposal was presented by taking into
consideration the demands of some parties and alliances that
mistakes and errors in voter registration should be rectified.
</P>
<P>
So far, the reactions of the biggest opposition Renamo,
which threathened to quit the first local elections since final
peace was realized in the country in 1992, are not available.
</P>
</TEXT>
