<HEADLINE> Jordan Denies Israeli Statement on Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordan denied Monday that the
Israeli government had informed the Jordanian government its
decision to assassinate anti-Israeli Hamas leader Khalid Mashaal
before carrying it out.
</P>
<P>
Acting prime Minister Abdullah Ensour told a press conference
here that they (the Israeli government) never talked to the Jordanian
government about their decision to kill Mashaal, who was seriously
poisoned in Amman in September last year by Israeli Agents.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon made a statement
to Israeli television Saturday saying that Israel had informed
Jordan that it intended "to finish the job" of assassinating
Mashaal, a Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement) leader operating in
Jordan, but not on Jordanian soil.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan knows nothing about it," said Ensour who is incumbent
Deputy Prime Minister for Services and Minister for Information
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Mashaal is a Jordanian citizen protected by the Jordanian
law and the leadership of Jordan and we will never accept
such threats to his life," Ensour told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli statements did not tally with statements made by
the Israeli government earlier that it was willing to regain
understanding with Jordan, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We denounce these statements. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs
will take the appropriate action," Ensour said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the acting prim minister said, Jordan had clarified
its position on the issue when Acting Minister of Foreign Affairs
Talal Sata'an Al-Hassan on behalf of the government summoned
Israeli Ambassador to Jordan Odid Airan on Sunday to inform him of
Jordan's protest and rejection to the statements.
</P>
<P>
Referring whether the Jordanian government will have special
measures to protect Mashaal from Israeli assassination, Ensour
said that the government would provide Mashaal with "moral and
material protection."
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli secret agents were arrested in Amman for trying
to kill Mashaal by injecting poisonous chemical into his left
ear before his office on September 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mashaal was rescued after King Hussein of Jordan pressed
Israel to provide the antidote.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Israeli relations sharply deteriorated over the
botched assassination attempt on Mashaal.
</P>
<P>
Israeli intelligence service Mossad chief Danny Yatom resigned
last month over a series of failed operations in Jordan and
Europe against Hamas, Iran and Hizbollah of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Then Jordanian-Israeli relations seemed to begin warming up
again when both sides exchanged some high-level visits and
signed some agreements to boost bilateral trade last week.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the second Arab country after Egypt to have signed
peace treaty with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
