<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Urged to Enact Law to Fight TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya was urged Monday to enact
laws prohibiting smoking in public places and the emission of
dark smokes so as to curb the tuberculosis (TB) which now is fast
spreading in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The TB cases in Kenya shot up from about 10,000 in 1987 to
42,000 last year, 40 percent of them associated with the HIV
virus which causes AIDS, a high-level African medical conference
opening on the day was told.
</P>
<P>
A combination of poverty, urbanization, malnutrition and the
escalating HIV situation has led to the four-fold increase of the
disease, said Daniel Kibuga, a senior official of the
International Union against TB and Lung Disease (IUATLD).
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Chief Justice Z.R. Chesoni, when addressing the 12th
IUATLD African Regional meeting, called the parliament to enact
tough legislation measures to curb smoking in public places and
to prohibit the emission of dark smoke from factories or motor
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The law, he argued, should provide a list of authorized fuels,
with the government intensifying public awareness education on
the need to keep the environment clean.
</P>
<P>
Where smoke is emitted from a chimney of a building, the
occupier of the building should be charged with an offense,
unless the occupier can prove that the emission resulted only
from the use of an authorized fuel.
</P>
<P>
The four-day IUATLD meeting was attended by about 300
top-ranking medical practitioners and researchers from Europe and
within the continent. The IUATLD, dated from 1867, is said to be
the oldest international body dealing with health in the world.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the meeting also predicted that by 2020 nearly one
billion more people worldwide will be infected with the airborne
illness, which is spread by coughing or sneezing.
</P>
<P>
TB is said to be the leading killer of adults worldwide and
causes more deaths than malaria and AIDS combined. Currently it
is estimated that two million people die in the world every year
and the threat seems to be increasing.
</P>
<P>
Treatments for TB are effective but they must be taken
repeatedly over at least eight months usually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
