<HEADLINE> S. Leone Rebuilding Challenges Kabbah: ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The greatest challenge before
Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah is rebuilding the
country and creating an environment conducive for foreign
investment inflow, the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG)
has said.
</P>
<P>
The process of rebuilding the country should start with the
re-organization of the civil service, the judiciary and armed
forces, said ECOMOG Force Commander Maj.-Gen. Timothy Shelpidi.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force liberated the country last month by
overthrowing the military junta, paving the way for Kabbah to
return a week ago from more than nine months exile in neighboring
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
"No foreign investor would like to invest in a country that is
not secure and safe," Shelpidi said during a meeting with Kabbah,
according to an ECOMOG statement from its headquarters in Liberia
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The commander called on Sierra Leoneans to cooperate with the
force to realize the objective of restoring peace, security and
stability to all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi was quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria Monday as
telling Kabbah that the western part of Sierra Leone, where some
rebels are still in hiding, would soon be cleared of rebel
activity.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for the speedy implementation of the
disarmament process to avoid arms ending up in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, he noted that arms could end up in the hands of
youths recruited by the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF), a
partner of the junta which overthrew Kabbah's government in a
coup on May 25 last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
