<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls for Return of Peace to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said in Djibouti Monday that regional leaders should make more
efforts to end the protracted conflicts in Somalia and Sudan so
that peace can return to the whole Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
"The conflict in Somalia remains a matter of great concern to
us all," he said at the annual summit of the seven-member
Inter-Governmental Authority of Development (IGAD) opening the
day, according to a Kenya News Agency report.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year-old president urged all Somali leaders to create a
conducive environment to "seriously consider restoring Somalia to
her feet."
</P>
<P>
On the same day, local press reported that Somali warlord
Hussein Mohamed Aideed, accompanied by top policy aides, visited
Kenya last week and left Saturday. Aideed's faction is one of
Somalia's strongest.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya can be an honest peace broker in Somalia," a member of
Aideed's delegation, asking anonymity, was quoted by local press
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Also at the summit, Moi re-confirmed that a new round of
face-to-face Sudan peace talks between the Khartoum government
and the southern rebels was scheduled to be held in Nairobi in
April and shuttle diplomacy had been done.
</P>
<P>
"Resolving the Sudanese conflict was not an easy process and
commitment to peace should be a paramount objective of those
involved in the long and protracted war," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called for the removal of hindrance to the free
movement of goods and services and set up an efficient
communication network within the IGAD, adding the body is mainly
a vehicle for regional integration and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Leaders attending the summit are presidents Hassan Aptidon of
Djibouti and Issaias Affeworki of Eritrea, Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi of Ethiopia, Uganda's Minister of State in Charge of
Regional Cooperation Rebecca Kadaga and Sudan's First Vice
President Ali Osman Mohamed Taha.
</P>
<P>
President of the self-declared Republic of Somaliland Mohamed
Ibrahim Egal arrived in Djibouti on Saturday ahead of the summit.
But both Aideed and him were unable to attend the summit since
Somaliland remains unrecognized as a country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
