<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Hails EU Foreign Ministers' Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday voiced its
satisfaction about the decision made by European Union (EU)
foreign ministers in Edinburgh, Scotland, on the Cyprus membership
talks which will start on schedule on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, acting Greek government spokesman
Nikos Athanasakis welcomed the proposal by Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides inviting the Turkish Cypriots to take part in the
Cyprus accession negotiating team as "positive and generous."
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the Turkish Cypriots and Turkey could abandon
their intransigence. The island's entry into the EU would also
benefit the Turkish Cypriots, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day informal meeting in the Scottish capital
Edinburgh at the weekend, both Greece and France withdrew rival
amendments to the British presidency's proposed opening position
in Cyprus' accession talks, which does not make a joint
Greek-Turkish Cypriot delegation a condition for negotiations or
make the resolution of the division of Cyprs an explicit condition
for accession.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the meeting, Paris had insisted that the EU
should freeze its talks with Nicosia if it was not possible to
negotiate with a joint team representing both sides of the divided
island while Athens had threatened to block the entire EU
expansion process if the negotiations could not begin as scheduled
at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup
backed by Athens.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the EU decided in Brussels to include Cyprus to the
list of countries waiting to join the group, but Turkish Cypriots
and Turkey opposed such a move by the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
