<HEADLINE> IGAD Summit Urges Support for Peace Process in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The sixth summit of the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) urged all
parties concerned to bolster the peace process in Somalia on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of the one-day meeting in
Djibouti said that the summit stressed the need to channel all
assistance provided to Somalia through the IGAD mechanism.
</P>
<P>
It said the ultimate responsibility of resolving the conflict
rests with the Somali people.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the conflict in Southern Sudan, the summit expressed
its profound appreciation for the on-going peace talks brokered
by IGAD.
</P>
<P>
It urged all parties to work together, seeking a ceasefire to
provide conducive environment for the next round of talks which
are scheduled to take place in April this year in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the summit reviewed the 1997
annual report and planned activities for 1998.
</P>
<P>
It expressed concern over the impact of poor infrastructure on
development in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
It called upon partners in development to expedite support to
the development of infrastructure especially in roads and
telecommunication sub-sector.
</P>
<P>
The summit has elected President Hassan Gouled Aptidon of
Djibouti as the next Chairman of the Assembly of Heads of State
and Government of IGAD.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Djibouti, Kenya and Eritrea, Vice President of
Sudan, Prime Minister of Ethiopia and Ugandan Foreign Minister
among others attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
