<HEADLINE> King Hussein to Propose Direct U.S.-Iraq Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein is to propose
to U.S. President Bill Clinton that a direct political dialogue be
opened between the U.S. and Iraq to iron out their difference,
Jordanian acting prime minister said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Abdullah Nsour said the
king will hold talks with Clinton Wednesday on a series of issues,
including relations between Iraq and the U.N Security Council and
the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hussein is on an official visit to the U.S. during which he is
to assess with U.S. officials the prospects for a permanent
solution to the Iraq-U.N. crisis over arms inspection, and a
breakthrough in the long-stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations, said Nsour.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks will focus on Jordan's "ideas" for an end to
the crisis in Iraq, Jordan's largest trade partner, in accordance
with full implementation of U.N. resolutions and the agreement
signed last month by U.N. chief Kofi Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had threatened military attack on Iraq to force it
fully comply with U.N. resolutions and grant U.N. arms inspectors
full accession to suspected weapon sites.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with U.S. officials, Hussein will also
emphasize the need for Israel to implement the second phase troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his Washington trip, Hussein made a six-day tour of
the region early this month that included talks with the leaders
of Egypt, the United Arab Emirates and Oman.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan paid visits to
the West Bank city Ramallah and Tel Aviv last Monday and Tuesday for
talks with Palestinian and Israeli officials on the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king's visit to Washington followed a string of
Israeli officials' visits to Jordan aimed at restoring bilateral
relations deteriorated by Israel's botched assassination of a
Hamas leader in Amman last September.
</P>
<P>
Besides peace issues, Hussein would also make efforts to
procure more U.S. aid for Jordan, Ensour added.
</P>
<P>
The king had undergone regular medical check-up at the Mayo
Clinic, Minnesota, and was ensured there that he was in good
health, said Ensour.
</P>
<P>
The king will also hold extensive meetings on the Capitol Hill
with the Senate and House of Representative leaders as well as
high-level administration officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
