<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD to Center Election Campaign on Jobs,  Social Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) today unveiled its election platform,
vowing to cut unemployment and conduct reforms to restore social
justice.
</P>
<P>
Seeking to replace Chancellor Helmut Kohl's center-right ruling
coalition in the next general elections on September 27 this year,
the SPD said it would go into the election campaign with the most
pro-market program in the party's history, with job creation,
fundamental economic and social reforms being the central goals.
</P>
<P>
To combat a record high unemployment of about 4.8 million, the
SPD pledged tax reforms as early as 1999 with the aim to cut the
lowest income tax rate from the current 25.9 percent to 15
percent, and the highest tax rate from 53 percent to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in case of an election victory, the SPD would also
introduce an urgent program to create about 100,000 jobs for the
young jobless.
</P>
<P>
The SPD also pledged to double state spending on education and
research within the next five years, and called for more flexible
and shorter working hours and more part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
Under the SPD election platform, which still needs to be
endorsed by a party convention next month, big assets owners would
face new tax levies while university students and families with
children could count on more state financial help.
</P>
<P>
On foreign policies, the SPD supports the idea of setting
mandatory goals for reducing unemployment and advocates European
Union-wide coordination of financial and economic policies.
</P>
<P>
It also backs the French call for a stronger European role in
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The next German general elections will put SPD chancellor
candidate Gerhard Schroeder against Kohl, who is seeking an
unprecedented fifth term in office since 1982. Results of current
opinion polls are all in favor of Schroeder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
