<HEADLINE> Inflation Rises in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The inflation rate continued to
rise in Kenya as February's underlying three-month annualized
inflation doubled January's to hit 26.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figure stood at 10.5 and 6.2 percent in January and
December respectively, according to the March edition of Monthly
Economic Review issued by the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The increase was traced mainly to the mounting costs of
transportation, the weak state of infrastructure damaged by
months of El Nino rains, as well as the hike in liquidity during
the last quarter of 1997, said the report reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The underlying month-on-month inflation rose to 10.6 percent
last month from 7.0 percent in January while the underlying
average annual inflation to 6.5 percent from 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The overall three-month annualized inflation jumped to 33.4
percent in February from 19.9 percent in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the overall month-on-month inflation
went up slightly to 12.3 percent from 11.3 percent. The average
annual inflation was 11.3 percent, nearly the same level as in
January.
</P>
<P>
The country will have to pursue a tighter fiscal policy so as
to reduce the month-on-month inflation to within the targeted
range of less than five percent by June, when the current fiscal
year ends, the Central Bank said in the review.
</P>
<P>
Among the efforts, the annual expansion in broad money supply
in the year to June should also be revised from 11.0 percent to
8.3 percent, said the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
