<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roads to Telecommunications Liberalization Can Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- It takes time and efforts to
realize telecommunications liberalization and problems won't be
totally resolved by simply copying and simulating the models of
others, a Chinese official said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Deqiang, vice minister of the Ministry of Information
Technology and Telecom Industries of China, made the statement at
the opening session of the Second World Telecommunications Policy
Forum.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the three-day forum hosted by the International
Telecommunication Union (ITU) is Trade in telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 delegates from the public and private sectors will
examine the regulatory and operational implications of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) agreement on trade in telecommunication
services, which entered into effect on February 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the Chinese delegation had been fully aware of
the trend in which the globalization of communications and
restructuring of the telecommunications industry are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
He said that his delegation had been also fully aware of the
basic steps a country should take in reforming its
telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhou pointed out, the liberalization of
telecommunications is not the only panacea for developing
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he added, in reforming its telecommunications
sector, a country should take such steps in conformity with its
actual situation.
</P>
<P>
"The reform of the telecommunications sector will involve a
series of legislative changes on matters in regard to
telecommunications regulation," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
"It is our hope that ITU members will find rational solutions
to these issues through cooperation and exchanges, pursuing mutual
understanding of each other's positions and observations and
seeking common ground while putting aside differences." he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
