<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Stresses U.S. Key Role in Peace-making </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Monday that Cairo seeks European efforts to break the
Middle East peace deadlock but it looks upon the U.S. as the major
mediator in the process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa was speaking at a joint news conference with British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook following the talks they held over a
working luncheon here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The two examined developments of the peace process, bilateral
ties and future partnership between Egypt and the European Union,
whose presidency is currently exercised by Britain.
</P>
<P>
"We should give a full opportunity to all effective diplomatic
means, whether the American, the European or any other" provided
that their proposals are based on equitability, the land-for-peace
principle and honest mediation, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
"There is the feeling of responsibility and the exigency that
the Europeans must float bedrock ideas and initiatives, but in a
way that does not conflict with the American initiative, which we
all support," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt and Europe saw "identity of views" on the peace
process, both calling for a quick U.S. initiative especially as
Washington is the main sponsor of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moussa acknowledged there will be an imminent U.S. scheme on
ending the peace freeze. Any further slowing of the peace process
will expose the whole drive to a complete fiasco, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"Even though the aspired progress has not been secured, we
should never give up the stage for a backward and extremely
perilous stance like that adopted by the Israelis," he added.
</P>
<P>
The continued failure to revive the peace process evidences
that Israel does not want to comply with the Madrid or Oslo
conventions or the land-for-peace formula, said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
He added that the current mediation efforts would manage to
have Israel to reconsider its policies.
</P>
<P>
Cook is bringing a European initiative to help end the deadlock
in the Palestinian-Israeli talks due to Israel's controversial
settlement construction in Arab East Jerusalem despite
international outcry.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who left here for Amman after a four-hour visit at the
start of his Middle East trip, had met with President Hosni
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day EU mission, Cook will also visit Israel,
the Palestinian self-rule areas, Syria and Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
