<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Decides to Intensify Money Market Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Monday decided to
intensify market checks to prevent profiteering following Greek
currency drachma's entry into the European exchange rate mechanism
(ERM) as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting of the newly-formed coordinating
committee aimed at checking on price and ensuring the smooth
operation of the money market in general, Greek National Economy
and Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said that the special
police squad was recently set up to combat financial crimes and
commerce ministry inspectors would intensify their checks.
</P>
<P>
Greece and the European Union's monetary committee agreed at
the weekend that the Greek national currency's new parity to the
European currency unit (ecu) was set at 357.00 drachma against one
ecu, denoting a 14 percent devaluation.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Greek business world and traders not to pass on
the consequences of the devaluation to prices by exercising self
restraint.
</P>
<P>
Repercussions for the Greek market would be small and
short-lived, he said, warning that those guilty of profiteering
would face extremely harsh penalties.
</P>
<P>
Greece's money market reacted favorably Monday to the Drachma's
entry into the ERM with the Athens general index closing 7.31
percent higher at 1,649.69 points.
</P>
<P>
Trading was extremely heavy with turnover at 41.1 billion
drachmas (about 4.3 million U.S. dollars) while interbank interest
rates dropping to 12.5-14.5 percent from 18-20 percent last
Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980317.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Mongolia Sign Three Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Mongolia signed three
cooperation agreements here Monday in a bid to develop the
existing friendly ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A cooperation protocol, an agreement concerning the reciprocal
encouragement and protection of investments and a convention in
the field of veterinary medicine were signed during the visit
of Mongolian President Nachangyn Bagabandy, who arrived in Ankara
Monday morning for a two-day state visit to Turkey, the first
of its kind by a Mongolian president.
</P>
<P>
Following the official talks between Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel and Bagabandy, Demirel said that Turkey wanted to
develop the relations with Mongolia in every field, adding: "We
never depart Mongolia from Central Asian countries and we show
great concern about its development".
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president called on the Turkish businessmen to
invest in Mongolia to develop the economic ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Bagabandy said that he was satisfied with
Demirel's promise to provide support for Mongolia in the
international platform.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Parliamentary Speaker Hikmet Cetin said that
Turkey regards Mongolia as a brotherly state in Central Asia
during his meeting with Bagabandy in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy expressed his hope that Mongolia and Turkey would
continue and develop their existing relations in every field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
