<HEADLINE> US Confirms No Resolution Against China to Be Sponsored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States confirmed
Monday that it will not sponsor a censure on China's human rights
record in view of the changes in that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The State Department Spokesman James Rubin said at a press
briefing that "We took this decision because of the steps taken
and the anticipation of further progress."
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that the U.S. decided to give up the attempt
to sponsor a resolution condemning China on human rights issue
just before the United Nation's Human Rights Commission meets in
Geneva this week.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the State Department confirmed the
press reports. Washington and its allies have tried for almost
nine years to seek such a resolution, but they never succeeded.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decision was taken after China announced last week its
readiness to sign the International Covenant on Civil and
Political rights, a move hailed by the Administration as a
"significant step forward."
</P>
<P>
"We believe this step, when ratified, will be a major advance
in China's recognition and acceptance of the universality of human
rights," Rubin replied to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China also agreed to sign the International covenant on
Economic, Social and Cultural Rights prior to the state visit to
the U.S. by Chinese President Jiang Zemin last October.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that China has released a number of
prisoners and invited the U.N. Arbitrary Detention Working group
to visit Chinese prisons.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China also agreed to create a U.S.-China
nongovernmental organization forum for discussion of human rights
issues.
</P>
<P>
Press commentaries here suggest that the U.S. decision was
intended to avoid further isolation as the European Union had
announced not to push for an anti-China resolution this year.
</P>
<P>
It is another significant measure taken by the U.S.
Administration regarding China's human rights record since U.S.
President Bill Clinton delinked the issue with trade in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"We believe they (Chinese) are moving forward to bring China
more into the fold on human rights principles, and we clearly have
seen progress in this area," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the decision did not mean that the
U.S. is satisfied with China's human rights record, vowing to
continue to speak out publicly about the U.S. concern.
</P>
<P>
China has said that it never intends to ignore the human rights
issue. But it has warned against foreign interference in its
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
On nonproliferation issue, Rubin said that Washington believes
that the Chinese are following through on their pledge of
nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
Defending the government's China policy, the spokesman
said, "Critics will criticize. They have to earn a living. We here
believe that we are doing the right thing for the United States of
America on China policy."
</P>
<P>
He refused to be specific about the date of President Clinton's
planned trip to China. Clinton announced last week he decided to
move up the visit to late June from later. No firm date has been
announced so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
