<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright to Meet Counterparts of Major Powers on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will meet later this month with the foreign
ministers of Germany, Russia, France, Britain and Italy to discuss
crisis in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said Monday the meeting will be held in Bonn on March
25.
</P>
<P>
High on the agenda of the meeting, which follows up the one in
London early this month, are how to contain the crisis and U.S.
plans to provide military training to other countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Albright had canceled plans to accompany President Bill Clinton
on a trip to Africa next week, thereby giving additional
prominence to the foreign ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
Since the crisis broke out in the region, the Clinton
administration has taken a tough policy towards Belgrade. It
supports more self-rule for the Albanians but not independence of
Kosovo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
