<HEADLINE> Dhanapala's Visit to Baghdad Successful: Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz said on Monday the visit to Baghdad by U.N. official Janatha
Dhanapala was successful and his talks with Iraqi officials were
constructive and scientific.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remark during an interview with a television
station of the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala, head of the United Nations special group to escort
weapons inspectors into Iraq's presidential sites suspected of
hiding weapons of mass destruction, concluded his first, four-day
visit to Baghdad last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he discussed with Aziz and other Iraqi
officials about ways and means of carrying out his mission.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the agreement signed on February 23 by United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan and himself is being implemented with
good faith.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq will open eight presidential sites to
the special group of arms experts of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) charged with overseeing the elimination of the banned
weapons and senior diplomats appointed by Annan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq formerly declared the presidential sites off-limits to the
U.N. arms inspectors, prompting the United States to unleash
threat of military actions to force Iraqi compliance.
</P>
<P>
Annan's mediation mission to Baghdad resulted in a deal with
the Iraqis, which successfully defused the crisis and averted an
imminent U.S.-led air strike.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the arms experts of UNSCOM in the special group would
be responsible for technical issue of the mission, and that the
political conclusion would rest with Dhanapala and the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
On relations with Gulf Arab countries, Aziz expressed Iraq's
wishes to normalize ties with them, including Kuwait, and exchange
visits to each other.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the relations would be based on mutual respect and
non-interference in others' internal affairs according to the Arab
League Charter.
</P>
<P>
Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990. Gulf Arab countries, notably Saudi
Arabia, supported Kuwait and joined the U.S.-coalition in the 1991
Gulf War which drove the Iraqi troops out of the sheikdom. Iraq's
invasion has scared its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Aziz criticized U.S. Congress' proposal to set up an
international court to try Iraqi leaders for war crimes. "This
proposal is ridiculous, and the U.S. Congress imagines that it
can order the world to act according to its will and intentions,"
Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Iraqi people are still suffering from the continuous
sanctions "which, in the viewpoints of all honest people and just
lawmen," is a genocidal crime which has led to the deaths of
thousands of innocent Iraqis every month.
</P>
<P>
The american administration insists on prolonging the sanctions
against Iraq, therefore, it should be responsible for the deaths
of those innocent people, said Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
