<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 31st Inter Arab Parliamentary Union Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The 31st session of the inter Arab
Parliamentary Union council opened here Monday with participation
of 19 Arab countries to discuss key regional issues.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day meeting, participants will mainly discuss
a number of regional and international issues, including the
stalled Middle East peace process, U.N.-Iraq deal over the weapons
inspection, Judaization of the holy city Jerusalem, Arab
solidarity and the establishment of Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session, Yemeni Speaker House of
Representatives Abdulla Bin Hussein Al Ahmar said the meeting
takes place at a crucial and complex phase in the history of the
Arab nation, calling for reviving Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, he said peace shall never be
established unless the Palestinians are able to create their
independent state on the whole of their national territory with
Jerusalem as their capital.
</P>
<P>
Nor will peace be established unless the Golan Heights returns
to Syria, and south Lebanon liberated from Israeli occupation.
Otherwise, peace will have no real substance, and one party will
exercise power over the other, exposing the region to danger and
instability, he added.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that "it is our prime duty today to reconsider Arab
boycott of Israel, and to cease all forms of normalization (of
relations with Israel)."
</P>
<P>
On the Iraq-U.N. crisis, he spelled out the necessity of Iraq's
respect of U.N. resolutions imposed after its invasion of Kuwait,
particularly those related to the release of Kuwaiti and other
prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
But he indicated that the continuing U.S. threats to use force
after seven-and-half years of inspection, under the pretext of the
existence of Iraqi mass destruction weapons, is no longer
acceptable, because Israel possesses mass destruction weapons and
nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the accord reached between Iraq and U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan in Baghdad last month on peacefully ending the
crisis, he called upon the two sides to fully adhere to the deal.
</P>
<P>
He also announced solidarity with the Libyan people, calling
upon the U.N. to shoulder its responsibility and lift the embargo
against Libya, imposed after Libya refused to hand over to
U.S. and Britain two suspects allegedly responsible for the
bombing of a Pan Am jet over Scotland in 1988, which killed 270
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
