<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Hopes for Russia's Help in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia believes that Russia
can play a very important role in settling the Kosovo crisis, the
Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Ambassador in Moscow Danilo
Markovic, commenting on the coming trip by Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov to several former Yugoslav republics,
said that Russia has supported and is continuing to provide
support for the territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Markovic meanwhile expressed regret that the Contact Group on
former Yugoslavia in its statement on the situation with Kosovo
approved in London last week did not set a clear line separating
"terrorist activity from legal actions by law enforcement agencies
within the bounds of struggle against terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group consists of Russia, the United States,
Britain, France, Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade has met the main demand of the Contact Group and
appointed a representative for talks with leaders of the Albanian
community in Kosovo, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
The group's decision should influence the position of Albania,
which supports the separatists, he said.
</P>
<P>
Markovic declared that the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia would
be glad if Albania regarded this problem as a domestic problem of
a friendly neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
It was known that the Contact Group called on the U.N. Security
Council to consider a comprehensive arms embargo on Kosovo on
March 9, when holding a meeting on the level of foreign ministers.
But many Security Council members held that the Kosovo crisis was
an internal affairs of Yugoslavia and that the U.N. Security
Council should not be involved in the matter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
